<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / London Stock Exchange: AB Foods pleases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Good results from Associated British Foods sent the shares upward, although
profit-taking clipped the gain before the close. Turnover, however, was a
below-par 330,000, with the shares adding 4 to finish at 479p. Pre-tax
profits came in at Pounds 338m, well ahead of the market range of Pounds
300m to Pounds 320m.
Most of the excess was down to one-offs, with operating profits only
marginally in front of last year's figure. For this reason, most analysts
retained their forecasts for the 1993-94 financial year, with Strauss
Turnbull staying at Pounds 310m. Analyst Mr Carl Short said: 'The shares are
worth holding on to for the eventual improvement in milling and baking.'
However, most food specialists agreed that the short-term problems in the
bakery division will probably continue to overshadow the stock.
</TEXT>
