<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow back on upgrade after a
cautious start
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER AN uneasy start, Wall Street posted modest gains yesterday as
investors put aside their concern over inflation and instead focused on
signs of more robust economic growth, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 4.47 firmer at 3,647.90. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 put on 0.64 at 460.21, while the
American SE composite rose 1.27 to 476.60. The Nasdaq composite showed a
solid gain of 3.22 at 766.21. New York SE volume totalled 234m shares and
rises outnumbered falls by 1,174 to 896.
The mood was decidedly cautious at the opening, as Wall Street looked ahead
to this week's reports on producer and retail prices for October. With data
expected to show a significant uptick in inflation, many investors were
sitting on the sidelines, bracing themselves for a further increase in
long-term interest rates later in the week, after the big sell-off last
week.
In the bond market, activity was light and prices drifted higher as traders
anxiously awaited the inflation data. After early declines, the benchmark
30-year issue was trading  5/32 ahead at 100 23/32 , to yield 6.189 per
cent. Prices at the short end of the maturity range were modestly firmer.
In spite of concern over the October prices data, equity investors managed
to regain their nerve near midsession, with cyclical stocks, which are most
sensitive to changes in the economy, showing particular strength.
In the automobile sector, Chrysler moved up Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 55 5/8
, Ford Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 61 1/2 and General Motors Dollars 1/2 to
Dollars 48 5/8 .
In heavy equipment, Cummins Engine showed a Dollars 2 1/2 advance to Dollars
99 1/8 , while Caterpillar was Dollars 1 ahead at Dollars 91 3/8 .
One of the session's most heavily traded issues was RJR Nabisco, which
softened Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 6 3/8 even though Bear Stearns upgraded the
stock to a 'speculative buy'. Tobacco shares had surged on Friday on hopes
of higher cigarette prices. Philip Morris also gave back some of last week's
gain, shedding Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 54 7/8 .
Paramount Communications climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 81 7/8 . At the
weekend, Viacom sweetened its takeover offer for the entertainment company
to Dollars 80 a share, or Dollars 10.4bn. On the American SE, Viacom class
'A' shares were down Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 57 3/4 but the 'B' stock
advanced Dollars 3 to Dollars 48 1/2 . QVC, which is under pressure to raise
its competing bid, eased Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 52 7/8 on the Nasdaq
market.
In the pharmaceuticals sector, Medco Containment Services rose Dollars 1 1/4
to Dollars 38 1/4 after the Federal Trade Commission announced that it would
not challenge Merck's Dollars 6m merger with the drug-distribution concern.
Merck dipped Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 32.
Canada
AN EASING of prime lending rates to 5.5 per cent from 5.75 per cent by the
major Canadian banks helped the Toronto market to break a three-day losing
streak, rallying in heavy but reduced turnover.
The TSE 300 index closed 14.4 better at 4,216.4 and rises outpaced declines
by 416 to 350 after volume of 68.7m shares.
Transportation recorded the day's biggest advance, 2.17 per cent. Golds
eased slightly.
</TEXT>
