<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / International Company News: Sculley awarded options worth
Dollars 72m by Spectrum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Sculley, the former chairman and chief executive of Apple Computer,
who last month shocked the computer industry by joining Spectrum Information
Technologies, a small technology development company, was granted stock
warrants now worth Dollars 72m, the company said yesterday.
Mr Sculley's 18m warrants were issued at a price of Dollars 6 1/8 .
Yesterday, the stock was trading at Dollars 10 1/8 . Mr Sculley is precluded
from exercising more than 3m warrants this year and the remainder can be
exercised over a four-year period.
'We believe that the arrangement reflects Mr Sculley's long-term commitment
to Spectrum,' the company said. 'The warrants were issued at the market
price when he joined the company, last month. He will benefit, along with
all Spectrum shareholders, only when the company performs well.'
Separately, Spectrum announced that its founder and two other executives
have resigned and that it has settled an outstanding shareholders lawsuit.
Spectrum said it has agreed to pay Dollars 1.5n in cash and issue 750,000
warrants at or above the current market price to settle the action. The
company admitted no wrong-doing.
The lawsuit was filed by shareholders in May when Spectrum's stock price
dropped sharply after AT&amp;T challenged the company's claim that a technology
licensing agreement could be worth hundreds of millions of dollars in
royalties.
Mr Sculley also announced yesterday that he plans to cut back loss-making
operations and refocus the company's communications services operations on
contract engineering and consulting services. He said that Spectrum plans to
acquire a small contract engineering and consulting services firm with
annual revenues of about Dollars 12m.
</TEXT>
