<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Deregulation for London buses dropped: Manifesto pledge
scrapped after pressure from MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has for the first time pulled out of a manifesto commitment
made at the last election by abandoning plans to deregulate the London bus
service in the lifetime of this parliament.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said yesterday the government would
proceed with new reforms of the capital's bus system, opening up more routes
operated by London Buses Ltd to competition.
But more radical legislation - which would have allowed any private company
to operate a bus service in London - has been dropped after a summer-long
campaign against deregulation by Conservative backbenchers and local
councillors.
Backbenchers, including Sir Rhodes Boyson, Tory MP for Brent North and a
former minister, had claimed deregulation would have led to road congestion
and fare rises in the capital. The abandonment of deregulation is one of the
clearest indications yet that the government will avoid introducing
legislation in next week's Queen's Speech which lacks the support of a broad
cross-section of Tory MPs.
In the last parliamentary session, several key areas of the government's
legislative programme, including the ratification of the Maastricht treaty,
were threatened by its thin majority of 17 in the House of Commons and the
activities of backbench Conservative rebels.
Several controversial pieces of legislation have already been postponed.
These include the Pensions Equalisation Bill, which contained politically
sensitive plans to raise the state retirement age for women, and the
privatisation of the Post Office, which was delayed partly because of
backbench fears over the impact on the postal service in Tory-held rural
constituencies.
Both pieces of legislation will not appear until the 1994-95 session at the
earliest.
Mr MacGregor yesterday announced plans to push ahead next year with
privatisation of the 10 London Buses subsidiaries and the tendering of the
bus routes. This could mean more private companies operating services in
colours other than the traditional red.
The transport secretary also said London Transport would move from the
previous system of 'gross cost' contracts to 'net cost' tendering, which
gives operators an incentive to attract more passengers and improve
efficiency.
Mr Frank Dobson, Labour's transport spokesman, approved the government's
decision to drop the 'crackpot idea' of bus deregulation.
'They simply dare not face the electors of London with traffic gridlocked
from Stratford to Ealing. Every sensible person will welcome this decision,'
he said.
</TEXT>
