<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Letters to the Editor: Better way of managing than cults
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PAUL MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Christopher Lorenz still cannot make up his mind whether the religion
of business re-engineering and the arrival of the 'horizontal' organisation
are good things. (Management, November 5).
It is undoubtedly of consummate interest to those 'high priests' to whom Mr
Lorenz refers, who occupy themselves by writing or talking about how other
people's businesses should change. However, is it really of interest to the
stakeholders in a 'staid' building society?
Our customers (as consumers) care about decently priced products backed by
professional and friendly service. As members, they expect
cost-effectiveness and financial strength. Employees want challenging and
rewarding jobs and like to be kept informed about the business. Our
regulators insist on prudent management and clear controls. The government
enjoys the tax derived from our increasing profits, and that 'bottom line'
is important to credit rating agencies too.
So does it matter what adjective is used to describe organisational
structure? I suspect big businesses end up with a 'mixed bag' which adapts
over time, but that is uninspiring phraseology for anybody trying to justify
a new religion.
However, quietly managing that 'mixed bag' to deliver improved business
results will perhaps attract more believers in the long run than some of the
new management cults which are strong on hype but patently unproven in
performance terms.
Paul Martin,
Leeds Permanent Building
Society,
Permanent House,
1 Lovell Park Road,
Leeds LS1 1NS
</TEXT>
