FT  09 NOV 93 / Arts: Whitbread finalists announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is the book prize season. Tonight the winner of the
Esquire-Volvo-Waterstone Non Fiction Award will receive Pounds 5,000. Next
Tuesday the Sunday Express Book of the Year will make one writer Pounds
20,000 richer.
Yesterday the finalists were annnounced for the Whitbread. Each of the five
nominated authors received Pounds 2,000. On January 25 1994, one of them
will get another Pounds 21,000 as winner of the Whitbread Book of the Year.
The Whitbread covers the literary field, with a candidate for each section.
They were: for biography, Andrew Motion for Philip Larkin, A Writer's Life;
for a children's novel, Flour Babies by Anne Fine; for a first novel, Saving
Agnes by Rachel Rusk; for a novel, Theory of War by Joan Brady; and for
poetry, Carol Ann Duffy for her collection, Mean Time.
The judges obviously have no prejudice against women. A feature of the
Whitbread is that its chosen novel hardly ever appears on the Booker list.
Theory of War tells of a white boy sold into what amounts to slavery in
post-Civil War America. Brady is a former dancer with New York City Ballet
who has lived in Devon for over 20 years.
