FT  09 NOV 93 / Vocational standards will be tightened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTMENT for Education is to tighten standards for new vocational
qualifications after a school inspectors' report found standards in the
pilot examinations for 16-year-olds unsatisfactory in some cases.
The Office for Standards in Education found in its report on the pilot
examinations last year that intermediate level General National Vocational
Qualifications, each intended to be equivalent to four old O-level passes,
were 'variable and in some instances unsatisfactory'. Advanced GNVQs for
18-year-olds, 'vocational A-levels', were 'satisfactory and sometimes good'.
The inspectors listed shortcomings including documents loaded with too much
technical language and imprecise assessment and grading criteria that were
difficult to interpret. Course requirements arrived late, so some schools
did not allocate enough time.
External verifiers appointed by the awarding bodies had to check standards
of work in vocational areas in which they had no specific expertise.
GNVQs in Schools. HMSO Publications Centre, PO Box 276, London SW8 5DT.
Pounds 3.50.
