<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Pumping shutdown starts in Durham
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Rivers Authority, the river pollution watchdog, will this week
begin studying the movement of underground minewater as British Coal starts
to scale down its pumping operations in County Durham.
British Coal spends Pounds 1m a year operating nine pumping stations in the
centre of the county, but the recent closure of County Durham's last pits
means there is no operational reason to continue pumping.
The NRA warned British Coal, which is obliged to give only 14 days' notice
if it intends to cease pumping, that it could face legal action should
pollution occur.
The prospect that the pumping of almost 8bn gallons a year may be halted has
raised concern that water might rise through mine workings abandoned during
the past 300 years, may become contaminated with metals and then pollute
streams and rivers.
British Coal and the NRA will assess the effects of reduced pumping on water
level and quality at the Vinovium pumping station near Bishop Auckland
before deciding whether to scale down pumping elsewhere.
</TEXT>
