<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Public 'puts high value' on landscape
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE rate environmental protection of the countryside as good value for
money, the government said yesterday, Bronwen Maddox writes.
The public is prepared to pay five times the current cost of conservation
schemes to save traditional English landscapes, said a report commissioned
by the Ministry of Agriculture.
Publication of the study follows calls by ministers for the costs and
benefits of environmental protection to be weighed more carefully.
The Centre for Rural Economy at the University of Newcastle upon Tyne asked
3,000 people about the value they put on the countryside and compared it
with the cost of the Environmentally Sensitive Areas scheme under which
farmers and landowners are paid to conserve some landscapes and habitats.
The overall cost of the ESA scheme in England last year was about Pounds 20m
 -approximately Pounds 1 per household.
Residents of the South Downs area of southern England indicated that they
would be prepared to pay an additional Pounds 27.52 a year in taxes to
conserve the appearance of the countryside. People from other parts of
England indicated that they would pay Pounds 1.98 per household for
conservation of the downs, even if they never visited them.
</TEXT>
