<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Retail sales show thin and patchy recovery: CBI survey shows
wholesale trade buoyant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLUME sales in the high streets registered a marginally higher annual rate
of growth last month, but they disappointed retailers who said that sales
were below normal for the time of year, and growing less fast than in the
summer.
As the accompanying table shows, the Confederation of British Industry's
latest distributive trades survey uncovered a marked variation in
performance in the various retail sectors. It also highlighted differing
fortunes for the wholesale trade, where sales were buoyant, and the motor
trades, where rising sales were considered low for the time of year and
where sales growth was only in the parts and accessories area.
Among retailers, grocers and chemists experienced a marked slow-down in
year-on-year sales growth between September and October, while furniture and
carpet stores, booksellers and clothing outlets reported big jumps in sales
volumes. Off-licences, which in September had reported a return to growth
after 12 months of year-on-year declines in sales, again reported falling
sales.
Mr Sudhir Junankar, head of economic surveys at the CBI, said the variations
reflected the end of discounting in some sectors and highlighted the uneven
nature of Britain's economic recovery. He said the survey, which polled 500
companies with 15,000 outlets in retailing, wholesaling and the motor trades
between October 18 and November 1, was 'a sign that retail sales are not too
solidly based'.
The CBI also reported 'stark differences' in the growth of sales volumes
among the different categories of retailers. All mail order companies
reported higher sales volumes compared with October last year. The large
multiples continued to boost their sales, as evidenced by a strong positive
balance reporting higher volume sales last month.
The number of large multiples reporting a year-on-year growth in sales in
October exceeded the number reporting a decrease by 31 percentage points,
unchanged from September. Small multiples, with a positive balance of 11
percentage points last month against 12 per cent in September, also reported
increased sales. But single outlet retailers reported an accelerating fall
in sales with the number reporting lower sales volumes compared with October
last year outstripping those with higher sales by 20 percentage points.
Retailers, wholesalers and motor traders placed more orders with suppliers
last month, although in the retail sector the increase came entirely from
mail order companies and the large multiple stores.
