<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Advertiser calls Mirror 'sleazy and stupid'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY, DIANE SUMMERS and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NUMBER of Daily Mirror advertisers yesterday reacted sharply to the
paper's publication of surreptitious gym pictures of the Princess of Wales.
Britannia Building Society, which had an advertisement in yesterday's
Mirror, described the paper's actions as 'sleazy and incredibly stupid', and
said it would review its advertising policy when its present series came to
an end.
The Royal Automobile Club, which was dismayed to find its advertisement
yesterday opposite a picture of the Princess in a leotard, was the first to
cancel advertising.
Mr Jeffrey Rose, RAC chairman, said: 'The RAC does not condone, much less
support, this unwarranted intrusion, and, in consequence, advertising with
Mirror Group Newspapers has been discontinued.'
The action was in line with advice given yesterday by Lord McGregor,
chairman of the Press Complaints Commission. Partly because the PCC has no
power other than the power of censure Lord McGregor suggested that the Daily
Mirror and the Sunday Mirror should be regarded as 'outlaws' and treated
accordingly by readers and advertisers.
Autoglass, the windscreen replacement company, said it would be dropping
advertisements from the Mirror 'for the foreseeable future'. It added: 'It
is important for our ads to be carried in papers that people respect and
admire.'
But WH Smith said it would be 'taking things to extremes to consider
withdrawing advertising', and HMV and Vauxhall said they did not take
advertising decisions based on the editorial policy of newspapers.
At the LA Fitness Club in Isleworth, west London, where the pictures were
taken, none of the 1,000 Pounds 500-a-year members had resigned, according
to Mr Max Clifford, the public relations consultant.
'There have been a couple of irate phone calls but nobody has resigned,'
said Mr Clifford, who is acting for Mr Bryce Taylor, the 39-year-old New
Zealander who owns a majority stake in the club. Mr Taylor admits setting up
the concealed camera which took the pictures, for which he is believed to
have received Pounds 100,000 from the Sunday and Daily Mirror.
'With my contacts these pictures will sell for Pounds 1m worldwide,' said Mr
Clifford.
The decision to publish the pictures in yesterday's Daily Mirror did not
pass unchallenged by the newspaper's management.
On Sunday, after the first batch of photographs was published in the Sunday
Mirror, and the condemnations were starting to come in, Mr David Montgomery,
chief executive of Mirror Group Newspapers, asked Mr David Banks if he had
any doubts about publishing. The Daily Mirror editor replied he had none -
at MGN the editor's word is final while he is editor.
As the Daily Mirror put it yesterday: 'Our motto always was: Publish and be
damned.' Last night it seemed everyone, from the Princess to the rest of the
British press - which now fears legislation - was ready to oblige.
</TEXT>
