<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Rabin in call to EC over exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL'S prime minister, Mr Yitzhak Rabin, launched a scathing attack on the
EC yesterday, demanding better access for Israeli exports to European
markets and more vigorous support for the peace process.
'The unjustified discrimination against Israel by the EC cannot be tolerated
any longer,' he said. 'We do not need sympathy, we need deeds and acts to
support those who have taken risks for peace.'
Speaking to the Institute for European Studies at the Hebrew University in
Jerusalem, he contrasted EC attitudes with those of the US. While the US
provided generous aid and its trade with Israel was roughly in balance, the
EC was running a trade surplus of about Dollars 5bn (Pounds 3.3bn). He did
not expect the EC to match the US, but it should let Israel compete.
The Israeli leader also wanted a more emphatic European stance against the
continuing Arab boycott.
The US said it had asked the International Trade Commission to investigate
how the Arab boycott of Israel has affected US companies, Reuter reports
from Washington.
