<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Private flows to Third World
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Private investment flows to developing countries jumped by a half last year
while the rich world's governments reduced financial support for the Third
World, according to a report from the Organisation for Economic Co-operation
and Development, Reuter reports from Paris. The net flow of resources to
developing countries from the OECD's 22 wealthy member states rose 23 per
cent last year to Dollars 165.5bn. Private inflows at Dollars 94bn, 51 per
cent more than the year before, outstripped official finance for the first
time. Official finance fell to Dollars 68bn from Dollars 70bn in 1991, with
aid falling to Dollars 55bn from Dollars 57bn.
