<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Franco-German plan to end Bosnia conflict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE and Germany yesterday launched a fresh diplomatic initiative to end
the civil war in Bosnia with a plan to lift sanctions gradually against
Serbia in return for extra land for Bosnian Moslems.
The Franco-German plan marks the first evidence of a shift in European
tactics away from total isolation of Serbia and more toward incentives for
President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia to end the war.
The proposal was given a guarded reception at a meeting of European foreign
ministers who remained torn between the need to take action to head off a
humanitarian disaster, and the danger of becoming embroiled in the civil
war.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, said it was important to
keep as many aid routes open as possible, but 'not by rocketing aid through,
and not by using force'.
Britain has around 3,000 troops in Bosnia, second in number only to France.
Though Mr Hurd predicted that more United Nations forces could be sent in
the coming months, Britain would stick to its present contingent, he
indicated.
At Mr Hurd's suggestion, ministers agreed to consider the plan at a meeting
of the Western European Union on November 22 in Luxembourg. British
officials said senior military experts would be present. 'We think this is a
good context to discuss the real issues and difficulties,' said one.
A copy of the Franco-German letter, obtained by Reuters news agency,
suggested the creation of UN-protected 'aid corridors' and the reopening of
the vital airport of Tuzla to fly in relief this winter.
It also proposes that Serbs should cede a further 3 per cent of territory
they control in Bosnia, which the Moslems have been claiming and which led
to the collapse of the most recent peace plan. In return, the international
community should offer Belgrade the promise that UN sanctions would be
lifted gradually.
Laura Silber in Belgrade adds: Moslem forces yesterday fired two shells on a
Croat-held munitions factory in Vitez, central Bosnia, as Croat officials
warned the attacks could prompt 'a catastrophe'.
In Sarajevo, UN soldiers yesterday escorted the first of 1,500 Serbs, Croats
and Moslems to be evacuated from the besieged Bosnian capital as part of an
agreement postponed for nearly one year.
</TEXT>
