<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Mirror row may prompt curbs: Threat of controls on press -
Princess to sue / MGN quits watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY, KEVIN BROWN and DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of press self-regulation was in doubt last night after the three
national titles of Mirror Group Newspapers pulled out of the Press
Complaints Commission over the growing row caused by pictures of the
Princess of Wales taken secretly in a fitness club.
Mr David Montgomery, MGN's chief executive, said the commission, the
industry regulatory body, was finished. He accused its chairman, Lord
McGregor of Durris, of exceeding his powers and behaving unfairly.
Mr Peter Brooke, national heritage secretary, gave a warning that the
publication by MGN of the photographs demonstrated the shortcomings of
self-regulation and increased the likelihood of statutory controls on press
freedom.
'Given the regularity with which we have been told that the press can sort
out these matters for themselves, I think this will have given a very nasty
jolt to everybody, and I think that makes it that amount more likely that
the legislation will come forward,' said Mr Brooke, who is expected to
produce a white paper on the press in January.
MGN said even though its editors would withdraw from the commission, 'they
will continue to abide by its code of conduct'.
The MGN withdrawal, which could fatally undermine the commission, came as
lawyers for the Princess of Wales said a writ would be issued today alleging
breach of confidence and breach of contract against the LA Fitness Club in
west London where the pictures were taken and against MGN which published
them in the Sunday Mirror and the Daily Mirror.
Lawyers for the princess won an injunction in the High Court preventing
further publication of pictures. MGN contested the injunction on the grounds
that it had 'done nothing unlawful'.
Mr Montgomery said the Daily Mirror decided yesterday not to publish any
more of the photographs after the Princess of Wales had issued a statement
through her solicitors declaring her 'distress and deep sense of outrage'
over the pictures taken by a hidden camera at the fitness club while she was
working out.
It is believed Mr Bryce Taylor, the main owner of the gym, arranged for the
pictures to be taken and sold them to Mirror newspapers for about Pounds
100,000.
Earlier, Lord McGregor had condemned the action of the Daily Mirror in
publishing the photographs. He said advertisers should show their
displeasure at an 'outlaw' newspaper by withdrawing advertising.
The Royal Automobile Club and Autoglass, the windscreen replacement company,
said they were dropping the Daily Mirror from their schedules but Mr Andrew
Brown, chairman of the Advertising Association, rejected the call for a
general boycott.
Mr David Banks, editor of the Daily Mirror, attacked Lord McGregor for
criticising his newspaper 'before he had even read our editorial'.
In an editorial comment in today's Mirror the paper says its commercial
rivals have 'played judge, jury and hangman'.
The commission will meet tomorrow to consider the issue of the pictures.
Sir David Calcutt, whose committee report on the press in January this year
called for statutory controls, said the Daily Mirror's attitude to the
commission amounted to 'total contempt'.
He said if the commission was treated in this way by an 'important
significant journal, then you have a real problem as I see it for
self-regulation'.
Advertiser calls Mirror 'sleazy and stupid', Page 9
Editorial Comment, Page 19
