<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / (CORRECTED) Budget 1993: Direct attack on indirect taxation
 -The growing lobby opposing extensions of VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 9th November 1993) appended to this article.
RAISING taxes on consumer goods and services is firmly on the agenda for
discussion as a way to narrow the gap between public spending and revenues,
but a range of arguments linked to the fragile recovery may stop Mr Kenneth
Clarke in his tracks.
For his first Budget on November 30 the chancellor is considering whether to
increase Britain's 17.5 per cent value added tax rate. He could also widen
the scope of the tax to cover exempt items including newspapers, children's
clothing and food. Other options are to raise excise duties on items such as
cigarettes, wine and beer.
These moves would fit in with the government's aim during the 1980s to push
the fiscal burden towards indirect taxes on goods and services and away from
direct taxes on incomes. According to Treasury orthodoxy tax changes of this
type provide the opportunity to raise extra cash without unduly weakening
people's incentive to work.
On Treasury calculations a 1 percentage point increase in the VAT rate could
bring Pounds 1.7bn extra revenues in the next financial year, while
extending VAT to food would raise Pounds 7bn.
Any new increases in consumer taxes would come on top of the imposition of
VAT on domestic fuel and higher petrol duties already announced for next
April.
In recent weeks, however, the Treasury has been bombarded with advice from
economists and lobby groups that - with demand still weak after the
recession - higher consumer taxes could deal a blow to growth prospects. A
secondary argument is that higher taxes on consumer goods and services would
push up the retail prices index, increasing the possibility that underlying
inflation would exceed the government target of 4 per cent.
The Henley Centre, a consultancy specialising in consumer spending, has
worked out how higher taxes would affect demand for a range of goods, shown
in the accompanying table. Factors such as the incomes of the people who
mainly buy the items listed and to the degree to which they are considered
non-essential 'luxury' items, mean that for a set rise in taxation, demand
for soft drinks would fall by a bigger amount than would breakfast cereals.
Professor Doug McWilliams, head of the Centre for Economic and Business
Research, another consultancy, said a rise in VAT or in excise duties could
translate into a shock effect that could hold back economic growth.
He added: 'Apart from putting up inflation, a rise in consumer taxes might
be an inefficient way of trying to raise money on the grounds that people
could decide to shift their spending away from newly taxed goods towards
cheaper products.'
If the chancellor ignores such warnings and decides indirect taxes must be
raised in the Budget he has had no shortage of views from lobbying groups.
Executives from about 20 of Britain's biggest retailers took Mr Clarke for
lunch at a London hotel last month to ram home the message about how tax
increases could hit them.
Mr Stanley Kalms, chairman of the Dixons electrical goods retailer, pointed
out how any 'messing about' with VAT in the Budget could affect the crucial
pre-Christmas period.
Mr Robin Simpson, director of the Brewers' Society, representing the beer
industry, said that by increasing excise duties on beer Mr Clarke would be
risking 'killing the goose that lays the golden egg' by stifling demand
causing tax revenues to go down.
Mr John Wilson, director-general of the British Apparel and Textile
Federation, said the imposition of VAT on children's clothes would cause
'considerable harm' to the clothing industry. The exemption from the tax for
these items of clothing costs the Treasury some Pounds 600m a year.
If Mr Clarke decides that higher VAT or excise duties are required, he will
need all his legendary toughness to shrug off special pleading.
 --------------------------------
 IMPACT ON DEMAND OF VAT-INDUCED
        10% PRICE RISE
 --------------------------------
                   %
 --------------------------------
Whisky            -1.5
Soft drinks       -2
New cars          -1.6
Carpets           -0.9
Instant coffee    -1.6
CDs               -0.7
Breakfast cereals  -0.3
 --------------------------------
Source: Henley Centre
 --------------------------------
CORRECTION
THE TABLE in yesterday's article on the effects of possible tax changes in
the Budget referred to the effects on specific products of a 1 per cent
increase in prices, not a 10 per cent increase as stated.
