<PROFILE>_AN-DKHDHAEZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931108
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (8): The agony and the ecstasy - Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE glass-making town of Marinha Grande in central Portugal workers
protest over the imminent closure of their factory, which has been near
bankruptcy since 1985. Some 500 jobs are at stake. But Mr Luis Mira Amaral,
minister for industry and energy, is not over-concerned.
Nearby, he has just opened a plastics factory that he is confident will be
competitive on European terms. 'We have to let companies that are non-viable
fall by the wayside and give our support to those that are going to be
successful in the single European market,' he says.
The incident sums up the agony and the ecstasy that industrial Portugal is
going through today. The government is letting non-viable, uncompetitive
companies die while it is saving its support, considerably bolstered by
European Community funds, for the success stories.
'We can't waste time or spend money on firms that are not going to be viable
in the new Europe,' says Mr Mira Amaral. 'We have to conserve our resources
for the companies that will be able to compete at an international level.'
It is not a question of Portugal's traditional industries such as textiles,
clothing, footwear, wine, ceramics and metallurgy fading away in the wake of
new industries and technologies, but of separating the obsolete from the
thriving. 'I don't believe there is such a thing as an obsolete sector or
industry,' says Mr Mira Amaral, 'only successful and non-successful
companies.'
Indeed, the initial findings of a study on Portugal's comparative advantages
commissioned by 40 Portuguese companies and institutes from Mr Michael
Porter, the famed Harvard economist, emphasise that Portugal needs its
traditional industries for new technologies and industrial sectors to evolve
from.
Portuguese industry is facing three principal problems: the international
recession has hit hard at a country strongly geared to exports; the older
generation of industries such as ship building, steel, fertilisers, textiles
and clothing are now open to competition for non-Community countries which,
Mr Mira Amaral insists, compete with unfair practices; and, finally, the
single European market has further opened up what has up to now been a
fairly protected sector.
Government policy for meeting these challenges is based on four principles:
using EC funds to support viable, modern companies in all sectors including
the country's traditional industries;
deriving the maximum industrial benefit possible from Portugal's natural
resources, particularly in the areas of forestry and mining;
making a special effort to modernise and develop the electro-mechanical
industries including vehicles, components, transport material and electrical
and non-electrical machinery; and
encouraging foreign investment.
But Mr Amaral emphasises that Portugal will be more and more selective with
the foreign investment it supports with incentives. 'I only want to back
foreign investment that contributes significantly to the improvement of
Portuguese industry,' he says. 'That means projects that improve our
capacity for management and organisation, develop our human resources,
contribute to diversifying our industrial base and lead to new markets.'
The minister points to the district of Setubal, south of Lisbon, as an area
that has been transformed by foreign investment. This is where the Es450bn
Ford-Volkswagen plant, the biggest foreign investment ever made in Portugal,
is sited amid a cluster of other big foreign projects. 'No other industrial
region in Europe offers the infrastructure, the closeness to the capital and
the climate of Setubal,' boasts Mr Mira Amaral.
But it is also true that the jobless rate in Setubal is higher than in then
rest of the country. Ship building, steel and heavy chemical industries have
been closing down and the workers aged over 45 that are made redundant find
themselves unemployable by the new industries that are springing up around
them.
'These men are too old to be recycled and will have to be absorbed by the
service sector or low-technology industries,' says Mr Mira Amaral. 'But it
is our hope that the new projects in the region will dynamise the growth of
services and basic technological firms to employ them.'
Officially, the unemployment rate in Portugal is a low 5.6 per cent. But
government opponents insist that statistics are not a true reflection of the
jobless rate and that a lot of unemployment is masked by part-time working
and unpaid wage arrears. Unemployment is forecast to rise to 8 per cent in
1994.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>PTZ  Portugal, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    ECON  Economic Indicators.
    ECON  Industrial production.
</TP>
