<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (9): Pig war makes a point - Problems of
the agricultural sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PORTUGUESE are not by nature a bellicose people, but there was no
doubting the anger of local farmers earlier this autumn as they attacked
Spanish trucks laden with pork from across the border.
The attack followed the Portuguese government's ban on the import of all EC
pork, in retaliation against the decision by the Commission's veterinary
committee to temporarily block all exports of Portuguese pork on health
grounds.
Portugal's pig war proved nowhere as dramatic or violent as other sectorial
wars within the Community, such as the clashes involving French farmers.
Nonetheless, it did bring into sharp relief the wider tensions facing the
Portuguese farming community as it is forced to knuckle down to the demands
of EC membership.
Traditionally protected from external competition, and operating in a small
market, Portuguese agriculture is facing competition from its European
partners at a time when it still has a long way to resolve its own deep
structural problems.
Portugal's agricultural minister, Arlindo Marques da Cunha, one of the
youngest members of the cabinet, nonetheless looks and speaks like a man
burdened by the demands of office. Portuguese agriculture represent 6 per
cent of GDP and 12 per cent of employment, and yet yields per hectare are
less than a third of the European average.
Five years ago, Mr Marques da Cunha interrupted his doctoral thesis on the
impact of the common agricultural policy (CAP) on Portugal at Reading
University, in the UK, in order to take up his cabinet post. But there is
clearly more work than a thesis still undone, as he is the first to admit.
'We are finding it very difficult to explain to our farmers that
protectionism was never a solution, that it brought us nothing but
backwardness. They don't want to hear it,' he says.
In the transition period following Portuguese entry into the Community in
1986, EC aid has been used to improve irrigation and communications and to
train some of the younger farmers in alternative production methods. From
January 1, this year, a final transition period has been under way, which
involves phased reductions in beef and cereal prices, together with cuts in
subsidies and the dismantlement of import restrictions.
Mr Marques da Cunha believes the two-stage transition period had made things
worse rather than better. 'In the first period, the idea was created in the
minds of our farmers that the EC was good just for funds. They were less
aware of the need to become competitive,' he says.
Over at the the Portuguese Farmers Confederation, the president, Mr Raul
Rosado Fernandes, a classics professor by profession but a landowner by
inheritance, does not strike one as a man in a hurry.
'The average age of farmers is over 50. It's going to be very difficult to
change their habits and their education. An economist told me you need to
get rid of thousands of farmers. I asked him: what do you do with the
corpses?'
The minister Mr Marques da Cunha, is, however, aiming to bring about a
gradual phased reduction in employment in his sector - to 7 per cent of the
population within the next 10 years, hoping that the farms that remain will
be larger and more efficiently run.
As for the CAP, he takes comfort in the fact that its reform 'is not yet
ended'.
'We need to bring more help to farmers in remoter areas. We need to
strengthen the regional dimension of CAP,' he says. Portugal clearly still
has some fighting to do.
</TEXT>
