<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Computers in Finance (9): An attack on paperwork -
Document management and business process re-engineering
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
PAPER is a curse. At the best of times, information goes missing when it's
most needed. For a financial institution processing thousands of credit card
repayments or registering mortgage applications, paper is the link with its
customers. These customers want to know the progress of their case, and that
can only be established by locating the paperwork in question.
So why not take the whole bureaucracy and store and process it
electronically? Customer queries can answered instantly by calling up a
screen.
The technology in question is document image processing (DIP), also known as
document management. Systems differ in terms of software and precise
functions, but the basic technology relies on optical disks compressing and
storing data.
The visual image is scanned by a device that resembles a photo-copier.
Essentially a serious relative of the compact disc, the optical disks are
arranged in a jukebox. A 64-disk jukebox can hold up to 3.2m pages of
information.
A powerful desktop PC gives every member of staff the power to call up
images in under 10 seconds. Abolishing paperwork through DIP has meant
getting a response to the customer in less time while also cutting back on
staff. But the current wave of installations have fallen in with the far
grander fashion of Business Process Re-engineering (BPR). The latest in a
succession of management buzzwords to spring out of an information
technology industry keen to promote the concept that technology is
indispensable, BPR is now intertwined with DIP.
The argument runs that DIP follows a document throughout the business. So
implementing a technology that cuts a swath through bureaucracy should
invite a fundamental rethink of the entire organisation and its structure.
The alliance of BPR and DIP has the partial blessing of Dr David Best,
partner in information management at Touche Ross. But Dr Best notes that the
challenge of BPR has actually hindered technical progress - 'document image
processing is not as widespread as it could be, because people find it
difficult to redesign their processes.'
Unisys provides DIP in the form of InfoImage beginning at Pounds 75,000.
High-end price tags are in the multi-million pound bracket. DIP is not a
casual commitment. At Clerical Medical Investment Group, documents have been
been consigned to microfiche since the 1980s. Now a Pounds 500,000 project
in the annuities department has pointed the way to a wider application of
optical scanning and storage.
Ken Hawkes, manager of the annuities department, finds the new technology
has made a difference to his telephone manner - 'people call in and say they
wrote to us in January and I can say 'Yes - I've got the letter in front of
me.''
Pam Webb, information systems business development manager, agrees that DIP
improves customer service. But she is restrained about leaping on the BPR
bandwagon - 'the image-processing hardware and software amount to just one
of the tools we will use. They are very powerful, but they're not the
driver. That has to come from the business itself.'
Pressed on the motive for the Unisys contract, she notes: 'If I believe in
re-engineering, it's with a small r'
Mark Churchward, manager of Olivetti's document management division, sells
Filenet. Billed as an image management and workflow system, Filenet has
grown over the years to include features such as handwriting recognition.
The expansion of its technical brief has been accompanied by the rise of
BPR, a vogue term unheard of when DIP products first emerged. Filenet
systems begin at Pounds 50,000 and stretch into the millions depending on
size.
To his credit, Mr Churchward is quick to offer a no-nonsense definition of
the phrase on every consultant's lips: 'BPR means taking a clean-sheet
approach to looking at what the business activity should be.' And
realistically, he concedes that BPR does not mean a blank cheque for
technology - 'it means looking at the legacy of the past and deciding what
processes really add value, as opposed to automating everything.
'So DIP has become the jumping off point for more fundamental changes - the
only way to use the technology to eliminate paper is to analyse the
processes. There isn't one right way to do things. It's different for every
business,' he says. Mr Churchward and his colleagues have weathered the
healthy scepticism towards IT adopted by most companies since recession bit
hard - 'we measure the benefits after implementation. A successful project
will yield a substantial return on the investment in technology. Our
business is guaranteeing that return.'
Four years ago, NatWest Card Services began introducing a 130-workstation
Filenet system to process letters arriving at its Access and Visa centre at
Southend. The number of documents handled daily averages 4,500, but can peak
at 12,000 for boom periods like the January sales. Over 10,000 documents are
retrieved from two 'jukeboxes' every day. Credit card account details are
retained on an IBM mainframe host, with 250,000 statements downloaded each
day.
The DIP side of this operation cost Pounds 2.2m. DIP has done more than
speed up access to data at Southend. It has put every clerk directly in
touch with the public. And NatWest has been sufficiently impressed to embark
on its own DIP software project.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
