<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Computers in Finance (10): Cautious view prevails
 -Technology investment slow-down in the insurance industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE BLACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS THE general insurance market starts to be shaken up by new technology,
older-established insurance companies in the UK are struggling to meet the
challenge.
A recent survey carried out for the Computer Management Group, CMG,
concluded that many of them were lacking in innovation and complacent about
customer service and competition.
CMG's senior consultant Mr Ian Bowen says that their attitude left them
exposed to an invasion of their market by banks and building societies as
well as by foreign competitors.
This view is supported by Ms Miranda Mayes, a senior business analyst at
International Data Corporation, IDC. In a study of computers in finance, she
found that insurance companies were putting relatively little investment
into new technology, partly because of the high levels of claims in recent
years caused by bad weather, increased crime and terrorism.
IDC found that 40 per cent of insurance companies expected to increase their
spending on computers this year, but only by 9.5 per cent on average. At the
same time, 28 per cent of them intended to cut their spending by an average
of 20.9 per cent. Insurance was the only area of finance in which spending
on IT was expected to fall over the next three years.
Many insurance firms saw profitability as a more important issue than
maintaining and increasing market share, the survey shows. Also rather
surprisingly, they put management information systems at the top of their
priorities for new applications, ahead of claims systems.
There are warning signs that they should be more concerned about market
share. Royal Bank of Scotland's subsidiary, Direct Line, set up in 1985, has
taken around 6 per cent of the private car insurance market in eight years
and is now challenging firms such as Norwich Union, Royal Insurance and Sun
Alliance for leadership in that field. It sells policies by phone, backed up
by a powerful computer system and marketed by TV advertising. The success of
the operation comes from giving customers a quick and easy way of getting
cheap cover.
The phone interview is based on a computer system which ensures that it
takes no more than five minutes on average. Then the caller can be covered
at once and a policy issued the next day.
Callers are asked to give their name, house number and post code; addresses
are then retrieved automatically to save time. Payment must be made by card,
not by cheque, which maximises the number of processed calls.
The range of insurables is limited somewhat arbitrarily but effectively to
exclude most apparent potential risks: sports cars and pop musicians are not
taken on.
The system cuts out the middlemen, enabling the business to be run more
efficiently and undercut its rivals. At the same time the culture of the
business has changed to Direct Line's advantage; people are far more
inclined to shop around for the best deal.
In 1987 the company branched out into household policies and it is now in
the top ten in that league. It has recently begun to diversify further into
personal loans, using data from car and domestic policies to assess the
risk.
Direct Line's system is run on a Comparex mainframe at its head office in
Croydon, claimed to be the largest online transaction processing operation
in Europe.
Mr Mike Flaherty, Direct Line's executive director, says that he and five
colleagues wrote the software in six months, using Computer Associates'
fourth generation language, Generol. It was based on IBM's CICS transaction
processing system and on flat files rather than a relational database in
order to get the highest possible speed of response. Direct Line's approach
has been followed in recent years by several firms including Churchill
Insurance, General Accident and Eagle Star. Mr Bowen expects that virtually
all the main insurers will have set up direct companies within a year.
The entry level cost for the computer system is probably around Pounds
500,000; a 200-user system might cost around Pounds 2m. New entrants are
mainly buying UNIX-based machines from companies such as Pyramid and
Sequent. Falling hardware prices have opened the business up to more
competitors.
The insurance industry is now asking itself how widely these techniques can
be applied. There is no reason to doubt that computers could handle it, but
would people accept it?
Sceptics argue that the motor policy market is an exceptionally simple one
and that what works there will not necessarily work in other fields.
Domestic insurance policies can be managed over the phone, although they
take slightly longer to set up than motor policies. But personal loans,
mortgages, pensions and life assurance may be a different sort of business.
Loans and mortgages, traditionally arranged by a half-hour chat with the
local bank manager, could prove less amenable to the direct selling
operation. People may be reluctant to take a decision which could affect the
rest of their lives on the basis of a short telephone conversation with
someone they have never met.
Undaunted, however, Direct Line launched a direct system for personal loans
in August, aimed at its 1.5m customers, after a successful pilot project
earlier in the year. Interviews are expected to take only take eight minutes
on average and a decision can be taken at the end of that time.
Next spring it will test a new system for mortgages and after that will move
on to a sickness benefit system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
