<DOCNO>FT934-9932</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DKHDHAETFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931108
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Computers in Finance (11): Aid to better decisions
 -Benefits of artificial intelligence and knowledge-based systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUNK MAIL is a contemporary curse. It afflicts anyone whose address
qualifies for a marketing database, and that appears to include most of the
adult population. As they bin endless leaflets, few people can sympathise
with mailshot senders.
Some companies, like the Sun Alliance financial services group, are
seriously concerned to get right letter through the appropriate box.
Sun Alliance is a member of the Department of Trade and Industry's
Technology Transfer Club. With a budget of Pounds 5.75m, the club nurtures
advanced technology, bringing together users and industry players such as
systems house Logica. Sun Alliance has volunteered to test-drive Autonet
Workbench, a smart program developed by Recognition Research, in
collaboration with Logica.
Autonet is an example of neural computing, a branch of software development
where the computer is programmed to follow patterns and produce a result
that is consistent with previous examples. It could be said to learn by
these examples.
Unfortunately the language of advanced software can be very deceptive.
Neural computing was christened after the thought processes of the human
brain. But no program can really replicate the complexity of thought. The
most advanced systems still learn by rote, and are limited by the data fed
in to them.
Sun aims to improve the response rate from mailings, and in the course of
that, reduce the amount of junk mail emanating from its financial services
operation.
The name of the game is spotting the correlation between information about
customers and products they have bought in the past.
'We only want to mail information to the customer who'll buy our financial
products,' says Steve Lamb, systems manager at Sun. Before Autonet was
introduced, standard statistical techniques were used. If this program
produces a one per cent improvement in sales, then the technology will have
made a significant difference.
Mr Lamb is adamant that Sun Alliance's venture into neural computing is no
gimmick. His department has spent time assessing pure technology, but that
is in the past.
'We did all the 'pie in the sky' stuff two years ago. We want to get some
money out of this and we wouldn't be setting it up if we didn't think neural
computing would become a standard part of our technology,' he says.
Sun Alliance is already examining possible uses of neural computing for
claims analysis. Encouraged by official backing and the prospect of real
gains, it is willing to take ideas out of the laboratory and into practice.
But neural computing grew out of the murky field of artificial intelligence
(AI). Such terminology invited inaccurate comparisons with the users' own
mind and AI acquired a mixed reputation. This legacy puts prospective
customers on their guard.
Mercantile &amp; General is the largest specialist reinsurer in the UK
underwriting Pounds 1bn worth of life and general premiums per year. Jim
Dawson, information services manager, has used software from Neuron Data to
devise Magnum, a program that takes the abstract knowledge of the insurance
underwriter out into the field with the insurance salesman.
'The problem with life underwriting is that it requires a great deal of
expertise. To discriminate between good and bad risks needs an underwriter's
judgement.'
Underwriting data has traditionally been stored in bulky manuals detailing
the risks associated with occupations or sports or medical histories. The
underwriter added a considered judgement to this cold data. Neuron Data's
Nexpert software provided Jim Dawson with the appropriate guidelines to
transform this mix of daunting statistics and professional nous into a
practical program.
The end result fits on to a laptop computer - 'we put all this data and the
judgemental expertise together. Then we integrated it with a salesman's
toolkit and let him take that experience out on the road,' he says.
Each Nexpert licence costs Pounds 5,000, but the real development costs lay
in recruiting and retaining the right programmers. Specialists do not come
cheap - getting the Magnum package out on the PCs used by Mercantile and
General's insurance clients cost upwards of Pounds 200,000.
The key to implementing such a system lies in 'diehard experts,' as Jim
Dawson sees them, 'the people who are able to get to grips with the more
arcane parts of program development.'
He is refreshingly candid in his references to the dramatic language that
suppliers wrap around these smart software tools - 'tags like 'artificial
intelligence' are too exotic and usually overstate the capabilities of a
product. We use the term 'knowledge-based systems' or KBS. It's more
meaningful.'
Barclays Bank has turned to KBS in an effort to make its commerical lending
more consistent. Lending Advisor, a KBS that started life on large IBM
mainframes, is under trial at 30 Barclays branches.
Developed by Syntelligence at the behest of US banks in the 1980s, Lending
Advisor merges historical data about the client with judgements about the
viability of the loan. The loan is then classified into one of seven
categories, ranging from unacceptable to excellent.
Lending Advisor does not come cheap. Licences start at Pounds 600,000. But
Mr Rob Turner, European business manager at Syntelligence points out that
big provisions for bad debts have made it critical for banks to disseminate
lending expertise widely.
'Commercial lending is a problem. We're providing a security blanket,' he
says.
Whether or not the customer qualifies for a commercial loan is still a
decision taken by the bank. Clever software can only reflect the wisdom, or
otherwise, of the user. But products like Lending Advisor do promise to iron
out seemingly eccentric loan decisions.
</TEXT>
