<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (7): Santa Claus image slips - Portugal
and the EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PORTUGUESE love the EC logos on their new car number plates, and one of
Lisbon's newest office blocks is named after Jean Monnet in recognition of
the European ideal. Beyond the symbols, however, a sense of uncertainty
about the realities of Europe is disturbing a country that has spent most of
its history struggling with an inferiority complex.
From his office in the Monnet building, the EC's representative in Lisbon,
Mr Francisco Sarsfield Cabral, is disarmingly frank about the collective
mood.
Mr Sarsfield Cabral who is a former adviser to the prime minister comments:
'When we joined in 1986, the EC was seen very favourably . . . it was an
insurance against communism, it meant living better, democracy, joining the
club of civilised people. Europe was a state of mind. Now I'm afraid that
the EC, having once been seen as Santa Claus, is becoming an escape valve
for every evil. More and and more people are complaining ..'
Complaints stem from the mixed economic fortunes which continuing membership
of the EC under the umbrella of Maastricht are bringing to Portugal.
As the poorest member state of the EC when it joined, Portugal has found
itself in the last seven years as the recipient of massive amounts of EC
aid. Between 1986 and 1990, Portugal received Ecu 2.9bn, representing 1.6
per cent of its GDP, in structural funds alone. Recently, the EC agreed to a
doubling of its total economic aid to Portugal to Ecus 18bn between 1994 and
1999.
Portuguese officials pride themselves on their country's reasonably honest
record in using the funds, although allegations persist about the misuse of
training subsidies by companies and some trade union officials.
The total funds have had a dramatic impact on the country's infrastructure -
improvements have ranged from irrigation systems to motorways and airports -
on training, and on living standards generally. But they have also
contributed to a false sense of security. Over the last year, the majority
of Portuguese have found themselves unpleasantly surprised by the harsher
realities of EC membership, not least the difficulties of meeting the
Maastrich convergence rules.
Portuguese officials, who 18 months ago were proudly proclaiming their
country's joining of the ERM as a sign of their commitment to the Maastricht
rules and to joining EMU at its inception, are having to take a more
pragmatic view about the pace of political and economic integration. They
take some comfort in the fact that Maastricht itself allows a measure of
flexibility.
Mr Vitor Martins, Portugal's secretary of state for European affairs said in
a recent interview with the FT: 'Next year will be crucial for a
re-evaluation of the convergence criteria. If the European economy begins to
recover I think we can live with the present criteria. But if the situation
does not stabilise, we will push for a rewriting of Maastricht.'
That the Portuguese economy was far from on course to meet the convergence
criteria was made plain in October when the finance ministry had to admit
publicly that the budget deficit had doubled from the original forecast of
4.7 per cent of GDP, to 8 per cent. The target date for cutting the deficit
to three per cent of GDP was put off until 1999.
Subsequently Portugal's finance minister Jorge Braga de Macedo has tried to
put on a brave face, insisting that his country remains, 'at the forefront
of those which want to be integrated in economic and monetary union.' What
is unresolved is precisely on what terms.
The present government has declared its opposition to the idea of a
twin-track Europe, with different countries moving at different speeds
towards EMU, but its own domestic economic mismanagement has effectively
ensured that Portugal will go through the door later rather than sooner, and
limping.
Former socialist finance minister, Vitor Constancio, believes that policy
should be allowed to reflect changing circumstances more clearly. He
believes that the Spanish peseta and Portuguese escudo are irrevocably
linked. 'If Spain wants to be in the forefront, it is difficult for us not
to fall behind her,' he says. At the same time, he thinks that European
union is best served politically by two speeds.
'It is clearly not possible to go back to the old European monetary system.
If we really want to move ahead to EMU, let the others go ahead first. We
may not be ready but we will get there in the end.' he says.
The broad thrust of official thinking, however, appears to be essentially
cautious and conservative: that present EC structures should be consolidated
rather than subjected to any major upheaval. Portugal's membership is still
in its gestation and has no wish to be orphaned.
Mr Martins is in favour of enlargement, and believes that the Efta states
will make the community economically stronger, and better equipped to deal
with Eastern Europe. He wants the present 'balance within the EC' to be
maintained. 'I am not in favour of constitutional change,' he insists.
As for Portugal's most politically active Eurosceptic, the orthodox
Communist Party, it does not have enough votes to push for a referendum, but
its union arm is flexing its industrial muscle in a way that could make the
government's efforts to achieve nominal and real convergence that much more
difficult.
</TEXT>
