<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (5): Times are getting tough for
exporters - The economy is highly sensitive to recession in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE experience of a small cork company in northern Portugal is a telling
example of how times are getting tough for Portuguese exporters. Just to
land a contract with a UK importer the company was obliged to pay a
good-will fee of Pounds 100,000.
'That kind of sweetener will take a long time for a small firm to recover,'
says a Lisbon-based foreign consultant. 'It's a clear indication of the
length companies are being forced to just to keep in business.'
Portugal is a small, open economy based on imports and exports that is
highly sensitive to recession in Europe. 'The European Community is
experiencing its worst recession since it was established,' says Mr Jorge
Braga de Macedo, minister for finance. 'The recovery is proving so sluggish
that it is bound to produce extreme anxiety and insecurity.'
But recession is not the only thorn in the side of Portuguese exporters. For
the past three years the Social Democrat government has maintained a policy
of a strong escudo. This, combined with inflation considerably higher than
the European average, has significantly pushed up export prices, hitting the
export sector hard and sending up a cry of protest from industry.
'The strong escudo stance is the key flaw in the government's economic
policy,' according to Mr Antonio Guterres, leader of the opposition
Socialist Party. But both the finance minister and Mr Miguel Beleza, the
governor of the Bank of Portugal, the central bank, defend the policy as key
to the health and recovery of the economy.
Portugal placed the escudo in the exchange rate mechanism (ERM) of the
European monetary system in 1992 and from the beginning of this year lifted
capital controls, making the currency fully convertible for the first time
in more than a century.
The escudo has suffered speculative pressures, which have cost it dearly in
terms of foreign exchange. But since the realignment of the ERM bands in
August this year the currency has remained reasonably stable without the
need for massive central bank intervention.
'We are going to hold firmly to the course of a strong escudo,' says Mr
Braga de Macedo. 'It is absolutely essential for us to achieve convergence
with our European partners and to participate in economic and monetary union
(Emu) with the first group of countries.'
'A consequence of the strong escudo policy is that Portugal is not able to
have an independent interest rate policy,' points out Mr Beleza. The high
interest rates needed to keep the escudo strong are another point of
friction with many sectors of industry - in particular, the difference
between prime rates, now at about 14 per cent, and the much higher rates
that the small- and medium-sized companies that form the backbone of
Portuguese industry have to pay.
A key inflationary pressure that could help bring down interest rates is the
level of wage rises. The government is seeking a social pact for 1994 that
would hold public administrative sector wage rises to zero and other sectors
to 4 per cent. Tax credit incentives have been offered to companies as part
of the deal as well as an 8 per cent easing of income tax bands that
officials claim will increase average family income by 1 per cent.
But negotiations between trade unions, the government and employers appear
deadlocked over an extra half a percentage point that the unions are
insisting on. Mr Braga de Macedo believes that achieving the government's
terms in a national wage pact would mean the difference between gross
domestic product growing 1 per cent or 2 per cent in 1994.
Others feel that a formal deal would help but is not essential. 'Most
companies are going through a delicate time in terms of liquidity and
profits,' says Mr Miguel Namorado Rosa, chief economist with Banco Comercial
Portugues. 'This means they will not be in a position to give significant
wage rises.'
Another inflationary pressure is the budget deficit. After the embarrassment
of a massive overrun in 1993, the government hopes to bring the deficit back
towards convergence with the rest of the Community in 1994 with a deficit of
6.9 per cent of GDP compared with 8 per cent this year. The key to this
appears to be improving inefficient tax collection and clamping down on
widespread evasion.
</TEXT>
