<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Computers in Finance (7): Hard line approach -
Fresh realism in dealing room applications
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PASCAL BERTAUD is responsible for kitting-out the City of London dealing
room of Lloyds Bank. Over the past decade his professional colleagues might
have approached this task with an open chequebook and unbridled enthusiasm
for the latest technology on offer. This being 1993, Mr Bertaud has no
intention of flooding Lloyds' dealing floor with innovative technology.
His brief is to find a system that works at a price the bank can well
afford. It is a strategy based on experience.
The current Lloyds dealing room relies on data feeds from Reuters and Dow
Jones Telerate mixed through IBM's early implementation of the Unix
operating system AIX. IBM PS/2 PCs are backed up by Stratus computers
performing the heavier processing. Lloyds spent Pounds 3m to get this
120-position dealing room up and running. It was a successful project in its
time, but is due for replacement. Lloyds has surveyed the market and
rejected the obvious and costly solution of a large off-the-peg dealing room
system. In the boom days of the late 1980s, these systems were de rigeur. In
today's more cautious climate, the bank has refused to embark on any
solution that might run late and over budget.
'I just believe that the big bang approach is no longer viable,' says Mr
Bertaud, a veteran of computer programming at systems house Scicon and the
merchant banking arm of Lloyds Bank. As senior manager for front office
systems he must reconcile the users' needs with a controlled budget - 'they
want a dealing system. The challenge for me is to update it at a
cost-effective price.' His strategy is a rolling replacement of the PS/2s by
Compaq and Dell PCs. He defines it as an incremental approach that will take
place over three years.
Mr Bertaud takes an uncompromising line with the financial systems industry
 -'I'm constantly plagued by salesmen. I tell them what we're doing. If they
can't add to that, then we're getting it right.'
This hardline approach has introduced Lloyds to systems not immediately
associated with complex dealing rooms. PC software giant Microsoft has
emerged as a pivotal supplier. Mr Bertaud's team is using standard
programming utilities from Microsoft to link dealing terminals.
The best-selling Windows PC environment provides the back-drop. The current
generation of development software from Microsoft, retailing at between
Pounds 500 and Pounds 3,000 per copy, allows the user considerable autonomy
in devising an appropriate local system.
Lloyds have built a simple but effective application that links dealing
positions. A deal keyed into one terminal will automatically update the
spreadsheet on another screen. The proven Microsoft Excell spreadsheet will
be the prime tool for the new dealing room.
Mr Bertaud has looked at the possibility of installing high-powered
workstations from Sun. In the late 1980s these machines were touted as the
box to match the dealer's Porsche. But many dealing rooms wound up with
excess power at the dealer's fingertips. Foreign exchange staff were in fact
quite content to operate a conventional spreadsheet on a 'run of them mill'
PC. As PCs acquired more power, the workstation has reverted to its original
role as a specialist tool for engineers and scientists. And PCs are
familiar. If you agree with Mr Bertaud that 'the only thing that matters is
being able to use the thing,' then the more comfortable Lloyds' dealers
feel, the more successful the implementation.
Lloyds will spend Pounds 5m-Pounds 6m following this option. Going overboard
with a Big Bang era dealing room would have cost perhaps twice that sum.
Telerate was in the forefront of the dealing room systems boom. Before its
takeover by Dow Jones, described by European managing director Dan Casey as
'relatively painless,' Telerate interwove data feeds in a variety of
ambitious projects. It expanded from providing information feeds to
producing dealer workstations.
Telerate stumbled badly with the Telerate Trading System (TTS). This
attempted to challenge Reuters dominance in the foreign exchange field and
sank in the face of a user base weary with technical innovation. Now the
company has re-entered the dealer box fray with Minex, billed as a complete
electronic broking system. Minex has been developed hand in hand with a
consortium of banks. Telerate knows the climate has changed. The current
generation of powerful PCs have redressed the balance in the customer's
favour, allowing the user to return to basics.
Technology is no longer allowed to distract financial institutions from
their prime purpose. Dan Casey claims that today's Telerate wouldn't dream
of hoisting an over-elaborate system on a client - 'the market asks for the
information and the product separately. We try to stick to the financial
community and their wishes.'
Tony Coveney is the director of Lazard Brothers banking division. When
Telerate entered a three-cornered fight with Reuters and financial systems
house ACT to upgrade an 80 position dealing room for Lazard, it won out by
dropping technical jargon - 'I insisted the suppliers all speak plain
English and avoided acronyms so I could explain our system to my fellow
board members' says Mr Coveney.
Telerate is carrying out a Pounds 500,000 rewrite of Lazards' software. It
will provide a Unix workstation backbone while the dealers attend training
courses intended to make the most of the PC software packages that have
become their standard tools.
Microsoft features prominently. The project was triggered by a desire to
boost dealer productivity without hiring extra staff.
</TEXT>
<XX>
