<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Computers in Finance (6): Push-button services -
Wider role emerges for new-style cash machines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOIA SHILLINGFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the UK, the Trustee Savings Bank communicates with 70-80 per cent of
customers through automated teller machines (ATMs) and Barclays says 200m
cash withdrawals - worth Pounds 10m in total - were made from its network of
machines last year.
Most ATMs only dispense cash, but they are starting to be put to new uses
and combined with emerging technologies, such as multimedia.
Since early October, Vienna-based customers of Creditanstalt Bankverein have
had access to five self-service machines from Digital Equipment which enable
them to:
Make giro payments.
Set up or update standing orders.
Get information on stock exchange rates.
Make deposit or account-balance enquiries.
Find information on other banking services.
The design of the terminal incorporates the latest multimedia technology.
For example, video clips describe the different services and when the
machine is used for payments or other transactions, a combination of video,
text and graphics guides the user through the system. The user responds
using touch-screen commands and a keyboard.
Norbert Cizek, retail banking manager for Digital Equipment in Austria,
says: 'In Austria, a money transfer usually costs the banks DM3; using the
machine it only costs DM1, because the customer is carrying out the
transfer.'
If, after a six-month pilot, the multimedia terminals prove popular with
customers, they will be used in the rest of Creditanstalt's 200 Austrian
branches.
At the Co-operative Bank in the UK, self-service machines are being used on
a pilot basis to encourage customers to open new accounts. At five of the
Bank's branches, customers can use IBM's Personal Financial Assistant (a
walk-in booth complete with self-service terminal) to open a current
account, savings account or credit-card account, or take out a personal
loan.
A telephone beside the terminal links them with a member of the bank's
Armchair Banking staff (in Skelmersdale) who can give them any additional
information they need. An application form can then be printed out in the
booth for the customer to sign. At 12 branches of Barclays, NCR Touchbank
machines are being used to allow customers to pay bills, transfer money
between accounts or find out about loans and mortgages. Similar services are
being offered on self-service machines used in the TSB Bank's Tyneside
banking pilot. Machines at 13 out of 18 Tyneside branches use graphics and
animation (eg a magpie to represent savings) to increase useability.
The National Westminster Bank is also testing self-service technology. At
its Surbiton branch, PC-based machines with touch screens give customers
details of travel, home contents, health insurance and mortgages.
Other uses for self-service machines include:
STATEMENT PRINTING
In Germany, dedicated statement printing machines are common, partly because
of regulatory requirements for customers to keep records of banking
transactions. The machines are also popular in Austria.
At the TSB, over a million statements a month are requested via ATMs This
has reduced the bank's administrative workload because most customers no
longer ask for monthly statements to be sent to them.
DEPOSIT-TAKING
Some ATMs allow customers to deposit money or cheques. But customers are
often reluctant to use them. Organisations such as the Abbey National and
the TSB encourage customers to make deposits by producing instant receipts.
The TSB has carried out customer training in the Tyneside area on how to
make deposits via a machine. ATMs are also available from IBM and NCR which
display an image of cheques fed into them.
ADVERTISING
Martin Hess, head of self-service banking at IBM UK, believes that UK ATMs
could one day be viewed as an advertising medium by large retailers. This is
already happening in the US, where some ATMs, typically those in shopping
malls, dispense money-off coupons along with cash.
So-called 'merchant couponing' has already begun in the UK. Customers of the
Alliance &amp; Leicester Building Society get a message on their ATM receipts
entitling them to a discount at Burger King or, in some cases, a free
hamburger. Martin Hess says such schemes could turn ATMs into a valuable
asset for banks.
LIMITATIONS OF AUTOMATION
Paul Swainbank, director of channel marketing at TSB, believes that in
certain locations unmanned automated branches will replace the traditional
branch. But he does not believe they could be applied across the board,
although they are cheaper to run.
This is partly because many customers still want to be able to talk to bank
staff face to face. Jerry Whitmarsh, head of technology planning for
NatWest's branch network, says: 'Our feeling is that people do prefer
face-to-face discussions when they are thinking about a major item of
expenditure, such as a mortgage or a pension. But a machine that produces
quotes is a good starting point.'
Substitutes for face-to-face communication, such as video- conferencing
links to bank staff, have not proved themselves yet. The Co-operative Bank
plans to add video-conferencing to its PFA system and the TSB is testing a
couple of NCR machines with built-in video-conferencing in Watford and
Newcastle. The customer is given a choice between pressing one key for a
quotation or another for an interview.
If they press the 'interview' button, they see a live video image of a bank
employee. Paul Swainbank says: 'Some of our customers were rather startled
and, to be honest, some of our staff were, too.'
Today, however, non-cash uses of ATMs are still limited in the UK and it is
notable that many of the banks' pilot schemes have been extended without any
definite decisions being made about when the technology will be rolled out
to more locations.
The writer is editor of the FT newsletter, 'Business Computing Brief'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
