<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (3): From militant Maoist to democrat -
Profile, Jose Manuel Durao Barroso
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARAH PROVAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Jose Manuel Durao Barroso has enjoyed a meteoric rise in Portuguese
politics to become number three in the government. Beginning as a militant
Maoist, he rose to become foreign minister, and brokered the 1991 Angolan
peace accords, perhaps Portugal's biggest diplomatic victory in recent
times.
At 37, Mr Durao Barroso is now the youngest foreign minister in the European
Community and, just a year after he took office, he is already one of the
most highly respected members of Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva's
cabinet. With a mixture of hauteur and natural timidity, he says the key
factor to success was being in the right place at the right time - and
facing challenges head on.
'Up until now, opportunities just came to me - and I took them,' he says.
When the Social Democrats swept to power with an absolute majority in 1987,
Mr Cavaco Silva invited him to become secretary of state for African affairs
and foreign cooperation, even though he had never set foot in Africa, a key
area for Portuguese foreign policy.
'The prime minister wanted somebody without prejudices,' he explains,
alluding to Portugal's numerous Africa veterans whose feelings often colour
their politics.
But it was more than that. His tact and ability to listen had already caught
the premier's attention. Later these qualities earned him the confidence of
Angola's two warring factions.
Mr Durao Barroso worked tirelessly to break the deadlock and bring the foes
together after 16 years of war. President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and rebel
leader Jonas Savimbi signed the peace accords in May 1991.
All excellent training for his current post. 'My experience made up for my
youth,' he says.
Ironically, though, he became foreign minister last November at the very
moment that his carefully-orchestrated peace accords were unravelling and
the Angolan civil war re-erupted more ferociously than ever.
With his youthful interest in politics, he was a law student when, in the
revolutionary fever of 1974, he began rallying Maoist rivals of the orthodox
Portuguese Communist Party. He now claims he was simply reflecting the
climate of the times rather than espousing any true leftist conviction.
'I was 18 years old and engaged in the first thing I liked,' he says. 'There
were only two political forces then. It was strange because I joined the
more radical.'
A stay in London in 1976 modified his views. He went to Geneva university to
take a post-graduate course in political science and European studies. The
sudden death of then Prime Minister, Francisco Sa Carneiro, in 1980 drove Mr
Durao Barroso back to Portugal and into the Social Democratic Party.
'The day after his funeral I joined the party. I never knew him, but greatly
admired him - he symbolised Portugal's struggle to become a Western-style
democracy.'
It was not until 1985 when Mr Cavaco Silva first became prime minister that
Mr Durao Barroso turned to the shaky politics of post-revolutionary
Portugal. 'But I felt the timing was right, and that Mr Cavaco Silva
deserved all our support.'
Somewhat philosophical about his present position now, he says: 'in
politics, even the best politician is never sure of controlling the
circumstances.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>PTZ  Portugal, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-9938</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DKHDHAENFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931108
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (2): Tension in the highest circles -
Politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE WEEKS after Mr Mario Soares, president of the republic, visited the
slum dwellings and shanty towns of Lisbon, amid massive media coverage, the
Social Democrat government of Mr Anibal Cavaco Silva, prime minister,
presented a multi-million-dollar package to abolish such degraded housing
forever.
To all appearances, the government move seemed like a hasty reaction to the
highlighting of a renowned failure of its social policy. The incident, like
many others, appeared to place Mr Soares in the role of leader of the
opposition instead of the independent political arbiter that he is supposed
to be.
The prime minister has never stooped to criticising Mr Soares for
interfering in party politics. But further down the Social Democrat
hierarchy there have been bitter accusations that the president does
everything in his power to block legislation he is opposed to and to lay the
government open to criticism over policies of which he disapproves.
The president has perfect credentials for being leader of the opposition
Socialists, who hold 72 seats in the 230-seat parliament, as opposed to the
Social Democrats' 136. He is a founder of the Socialist Party and three
times prime minister of Socialist-led governments.
But - now in his second and final five-year term - he was elected on a
platform of being 'president of all the Portuguese', committed to Portugal's
constitutional system of being a neutral referee of the political system.
Mr Soares is accused by many of taking on the role of a one-man opposition.
He has achieved this in various ways: by speaking out against social
injustice and poverty, which the government has taken as direct criticism of
its own policies, and, chiefly, by blocking legislation by vetoing it or
sending it to the constitutional court for vetting to decide whether it
contravenes the constitution.
Mr Soares has done this with a series of important laws and has been
vindicated by the decision of the court on most occasions.
The question arises: who is responsible for the open tension that often
arises between president and government? For the Social Democrat ranks, Mr
Soares is the clear protagonist, using his power to make up for a political
vacuum left by a weak and divided Socialist Party that has failed to take
advantage of the Social Democrats' weaknesses.
But for the Socialists, it is the government that has adopted a deliberate
policy of provoking Mr Soares. 'The president has fulfilled his roll with
absolute neutrality,' says Mr Antonio Guterres, leader of the Socialist
Party. 'But the government has adopted a systematic policy of seeking
confrontation with the president, with the aim of both undermining the role
of Mr Soares and at the same time denigrating the Socialist Party for
allegedly failing to be an adequate opposition.'
The two main parties are running neck-and-neck in the opinion polls. This
should be comforting for Mr Cavaco Silva, considering he is at mid-term, the
country has lapsed into recession and new independent television stations
and newspapers are revealing cases of alleged corruption at high levels.
But it also has to be remembered that the Socialists have caught up 20
percentage points in the polls since the last general election in 1991.
The poll of polls will take the form of nationwide municipal elections in
December. The Socialists inflicted a humiliating defeat on the Social
Democrats in the last local government poll in a backlash vote against the
government. To maintain any semblance of a firm opposition in this election
the Socialists will have to hold on to key cities such as Oporto and Lisbon,
where they are running in a coalition with the old-guard Communist Party.
Looking ahead to the next general election in 1995, the recessive economic
climate is likely to push unemployment and Portugal's degraded education,
health and social security systems to the fore as voting issues. This could
be enough to prevent the Social Democrats winning a third, consecutive
overall majority.
'In that climate,' forecasts Mr Guterres, 'Mr Cavaco Silva may decide to cut
his losses and give up a bid to be re-elected prime minister and instead run
for president in 1996.'
</TEXT>
