<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Survey of Portugal (1): The glitter starts to fade - Big
improvements in the country's infrastructure testify to the benefits of EC
membership. The creation of the single market has, however, brought
agriculture and industry face to face with competition from more advanced
neighbours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TIDE of euphoria that has buoyed Portugal since it joined the European
Community in 1986 is ebbing fast. The high growth rates of the late 1980s
have given way to recession, and the political stability which cemented
business confidence for more than a decade can no longer be taken for
granted.
The EC has lost its glitter as companies grapple with competition within a
single market. Unemployment is rising and foreign investors no longer find
the country almost irresistible.
'The pessimism that is gripping Portugal is a natural reaction to less
spectacular rates of growth,' says Mr William Cunningham, a Lisbon-based
partner with consultants Arthur Andersen. 'Portugal could not go on being
the star of European growth forever. The pace of economic development is
having to be reined in.'
One of the most telling signs of Portugal's economic slowdown was a massive
budgetary overrun in 1993.
This brought embarrassment for the centre-right Social Democrat government
of Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva and deep concern for the business
community.
In October, Mr Jorge Braga de Macedo, finance minister, was forced to
announce a supplementary budget for 1993 because low tax revenue and higher
than forecast social security spending had almost doubled the budget deficit
compared with original forecasts.
This year's budget deficit is now forecast at Es1,000bn (Dollars 5.8bn), 8
per cent of gross domestic product, against an original forecast of Es576bn,
4.6 per cent of GDP.
The forecast deficit for 1994 is Es776 billion, 6.9 per cent of GDP. 'The
budget deficit is our most acute worry,' says Mr Miguel Beleza, governor of
the Bank of Portugal, the central bank. 'No governor can be happy with a 7
per cent deficit.'
Mr Beleza's dissatisfaction with budgetary performance appears to reflect a
sharp difference of opinion between the finance ministry and the central
bank over key areas of economic policy.
But Mr Braga de Macedo is far from bowed by the heavy deficit. He points out
that EC economies are forecast to contract by about 0.5 percentage point
this year - a far cry from earlier hopes that the 3 per cent growth rates of
the late 1980s could be maintained. Portugal will continue to out-perform
the Community as a whole, he points out, and the government remains
committed to the goal of economic convergence and to participation in
economic and monetary union (Emu), currently set for 1997 or 1999.
For the average Portuguese worker, there is a concrete goal behind the ideal
of convergence: wages moving towards the same level as those elsewhere in
Europe. In the heyday of Portuguese growth, the philosophy behind pay
negotiations was that wages could catch up with the rest of Europe, but that
objective has had to be put aside, at least temporarily, as the recession
bites.
'For our firms to remain competitive in the single market, we simply cannot
offer workers more than main trading partners such as Germany, Spain and
France,' says Mr Braga de Macedo.
In tense negotiations for a national wage pact in 1994, the government is
offering public administration employees a zero rise and others workers four
per cent.
The talks appear likely to collapse over a difference of half a percentage
point which is preventing unions, employers and government from reaching a
deal.
The convergence of wage levels is only one aspect of Portugal's relations
with the EC that is beginning to turn sour. The Portuguese have been fervent
Europeans since membership, and many vital new infrastructure projects bear
witness to the billions of Ecus that have poured in from Brussels since
1986.
But the opening of the single European market this year has brought industry
and, particularly, Portugal's backward agricultural sector face to face with
the reality of competition with far more advanced neighbours.
Trucks carrying Spanish pork have been attacked and fish, fruit and milk
dumped in the streets as farmers protest against cheaper, better quality
goods from abroad.
'The vast majority of the Portuguese are strongly pro-European,' says Mr
Antonio Guterres, the leader of the main opposition party, the Socialists.
'European policy is an area in which the two main parties are in basic
agreement.' But clearly Brussels is no longer seen only as the bountiful
provider it once used to be.
Socialist party policy differs only slightly from the Social Democrats in
other areas, too. This has undermined Mr Guterres' attempts to present the
Socialists as a clear alternative to the Social Democrats in government.
Critics say the Socialists are too fragmented and have failed to take
sufficient advantage of the Social Democrats' weaknesses to make a viable
bid for power.
The Socialist Party is also overshadowed by the figure of Mr Mario Soares,
the president of the republic and a former Socialist leader. The president
is often ironically referred to as the leader of the opposition.
As president Mr Soares is officially supposed to remain above party
politics. But in view of his capacity to veto government legislation, to
send laws to the constitutional court for vetting and to expose social ills
in his tours of the country, the president is often seen by the prime
minister as one of the forcas de bloqueio, or opposing forces, that are
supposedly hampering the government's reform programme.
By the time of the next general election in 1995, Mr Cavaco Silva will have
ruled Portugal with an overall parliamentary majority for a decade. The key
question is whether he can win a third consecutive majority, particularly in
a markedly less favourable economic climate.
In two recent television debates, the prime minister polled only a 45 per
cent approval rating against 80 per cent for Mr Guterres. The next real test
of the two main parties' standing will come in local elections in December,
when the Socialists will be fighting to hold on to Lisbon, Oporto, and other
cities which they won in a backlash vote against Mr Cavaco Silva in the last
election.
As voters face up to economic realities, their attention is likely to turn
away from new motorways, bridges, and shiny bank frontages, built during the
years of economic expansion, to the state of Portugal's health, education
and social security systems.
The lack of resources for improving these services will influence the
electorate, says Mr Cunningham.
Many analysts think it is unlikely the Social Democrats will win a third
overall majority, and believe they will be forced into coalition with a
small right-wing party.
But gloom and uncertainty are not universal sentiments in Portugal. A
thriving cultural scene has blossomed with economic development, led by a
younger generation less concerned with politics than their predecessors of
the 1970s and early 1980s.
Lisbon has been elected European Capital of Culture in 1994. Four years
later the city will stage a Universal Exhibition. If all goes to plan, Expo
'98 will transform derelict dock lands to the east of the city into a
thriving centre of the arts.
By then - provided the Portuguese and EC economies have attained higher
growth rates - the country should have something to celebrate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
