<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / No more winner-takes-all: Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If there is a fashionable new buzz idea these days, it is the globalisation
of the world economy. Ultra-liberals inevitably think it is an unmitigated
blessing; the rest of us may wonder at the political and social price we are
already paying.
Imperious reality is not in doubt, however. The internationalisation of
world finance is overwhelming the old demarcations between national
financial markets. The competition of low-cost, high-tech producers in Asia
is challenging the survival of slower-moving traditional producers in Europe
and the US. And global competitive pressures threaten to sweep away Europe's
costly social welfare systems.
The political implications are disturbing. Democracy is more or less
established in the west, and precariously foisted on other parts of the
world, apart from China. Yet the globalisation of economics undermines the
ability of democratic governments even to influence the essential conditions
affecting their voters.
Key factors are, in the short run, the interest rate policy of the
Bundesbank, in the long run, the harvesting of the rain forests of Brazil;
in neither case can democratically elected national governments affect the
outcome.
The answer to this mis-match between the traditional nation state and the
modern global economy, according to David Held*, professor of politics at
the Open University, is to extend active democracy up the international
hierarchy, from the nation state to the global system.
The starting point for what Mr Held terms 'the cosmopolitan model of
democracy' would be a far-reaching reform of the United Nations, including
the creation of a second UN chamber, compulsory jurisdiction for the
International Court, and the establishment of a small, accountable,
international police force.
Mr Held makes no attempt to deny the immense conceptual and practical
difficulties of such an internationalisation of democracy. But to say that
his ideas are utopian is not a serious objection: only a utopian would have
imagined the creation of the UN, the World Bank or the European Community,
only a utopian would have predicted the collapse of communism, and only a
utopian would have imagined the information revolution which is at the root
of the globalisation of the world economy.
The trouble with Mr Held's ideas is not that they are over-optimistic, but
that they are over-global. The nation state will remain for the foreseeable
future the fundamental building block of democratic politics. The problem he
identifies is a crisis of loss of national political effectiveness, and
therefore loss of democratic legitimacy. But only part of the solution lies
in the creation of new institutions at global or regional level: the more
urgent practical tasks are, first, to make national democracies work better
and, second, to improve co-operative democracy between local groups of
states.
In the EC, for example, there is a glaring problem of political legitimacy,
which showed up in the national ratification debates on Maastricht. But
contrary to the usual Euro-babble, it has virtually nothing to do with the
shortfall in the powers of the European Parliament, and everything to do
with the inadequate legitimacy of national political systems. Voters do not
trust national politicians, and above all they do not trust them to
safeguard the national interest in dealing with Europe.
With the politicians we have, there may be no way of regaining that trust.
But there is a sure way of forfeiting it: to persist in a voting system in
the European Council of Ministers that gives several times as much weight to
the interests of a Luxembourger as to those of an Italian or German.
No national democracy would tolerate such inequality in constituencies or
voting weights for national elections; and unless the Community starts to
think in terms of real voters, rather than in terms of artificially weighted
member states, the entire operation will be closed down by the German
constitutional court, and quite right too.
This is an indication of the Community's development. In 1958 it was
essential to protect the little member states; today it is essential to
protect the voters.
The same principle applies to Northern Ireland; but the solution is quite
the reverse. Britain and Ireland are both being held to ransom by two
infinitesimally tiny minorities. The power of these barbarous extremists
does not really come from bombs and guns, but from the belief, relentlessly
fostered by every British politician, that this is a political system where
the winner takes all. The IRA believes that one last murder will make Ulster
wholly and permanently Irish; the UDA that one last murder will keep Ulster
wholly and permanently British.
There is only one logical strategy for defeating the murderers; and that is
a treaty between Britain and Ireland, which would virtually amount to a
condominium over the province's future, and which would rule out, for ever,
the feasibility of winner-take-all.
Some people would say that proportionality and democracy should be extended
not just upwards to the UN and the EC, but downwards to the nation states;
for example, to Britain's national electoral system. But, of course, that is
just the absurd imagining of people who do not understand the deep beauty of
British democracy.
* Democracy and the New International Order, by David Held, Institute for
Public Policy Research, 30 Southampton Street, London WC2, 30 pages, Pounds
2.95
Ian Davidson will be on sabbatical until the end of this year
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
