<PROFILE>_AN-DKHDHAEDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931108
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / New Zealanders turn the tables: The electorate could take
only so much
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When choice comes down to the devil or the deep blue sea, it is time to
change the ground-rules. That, at any rate, was the message emanating from
New Zealand on Saturday night - and it should give 'free market' reformers
the world over pause for thought.
Throughout this election, New Zealanders have been in a bind. Nine years
ago, they voted in a Labour government which radically overhauled the
country's economic structures and institutions. It did away with decades of
heavy protectionism, deregulated financial markets, and began a stream of
privatisations. In 1990, the electorate switched allegiance to the National
Party, which attacked the country's cradle-to-grave welfare system,
replacing 'universalism' with targeted arrangements aimed at aiding the most
needy.
Both governments acted in the name of international competitiveness and
financial prudence, and the speed and extent of New Zealand's reforms won
widespread approbation overseas. But many New Zealanders view the results
differently. They see high unemployment; a rising crime rate which,
arguably, is associated with the teenage jobless figures; hospital
waiting-lists; and deteriorating access to decent education.
So, now that the politicians have changed everything else, New Zealanders
have decided to change the politicians.
Not just the faces, but the entire way of conducting politics. The one
decisive vote delivered on Saturday night was for a 'mixed member
proportional' electoral system to replace the British-style,
'first-past-the-post' arrangement. Under MMP, the single-chamber parliament
will be enlarged from 99 to 120 seats, but only half the incumbents will
represent specific electorates. The remainder will be drawn from party
lists, so that the composition of parliament overall reflects the popular
vote.
MMP was endorsed this weekend despite a massive advertising campaign by its
opponents. Virtually all parts of the country were supportive. Moreover, the
MMP decision came after an abnormally high voter turnout.
It is easy to see why MMP, for all its obvious frailties, has triumphed.
Under the new system, New Zealanders have been told, two things will happen.
First, minority parties who get a significant share of the popular vote will
find that they have corresponding representation in parliament. Second, and
largely because of this, a process of consensus politics will have to
evolve.
This, in turn, should prevent the high-handed behaviour displayed by the two
main parties over the past nine years. Both National and Labour pushed
through their reforms without having a majority of the popular vote.
Neither, moreover, had fully declared their intentions beforehand.
Unfortunately, by also delivering a hung parliament under the current
first-past-the-post rules, New Zealanders have ensured that consultative
government starts this morning, rather than with an MMP election in three
years' time. This will be messy - though quite how messy is hard to
determine at this stage.
For a start, the final count has yet to be established. Because of the
number of New Zealanders working overseas, 'special votes' account for about
10 per cent of the total cast. It will be another two weeks before these
results are added in. But some seats, held on wafer-thin margins at present,
could change hands as a result. A majority of under 400 votes pertains in
nine electorates, and in the case of Auckland's Birkenhead, it is just 34.
Second, it is unclear what structure of alliances - if any - will be worked
out between National and Labour, and the two minority parties which have a
couple of seats each. Jim Anderton, whose Alliance party won 18.7 per cent
of the popular vote, says that he will not 'frustrate the party that has the
most seats from governing'. Even so, given the party differences over
welfare issues and labour market reform, many pundits suspect that a
confidence vote is eventually inevitable.
The simplest solution would be to call another election under the new MMP
rules immediately. For practical reasons, this is not an option. Boundary
lines must be redrawn; rules drawn up to govern the party lists; Maori
voters re-enrolled and the number of Maori seats determined. All this, it is
estimated, will take at least 18 months - although some think the timetable
is unnecessarily long. So if New Zealanders were looking for stability, they
have shot themselves in the foot.
But the rest of the world, so envious of New Zealand's rapid reform process,
may like to reflect on the election's lessons. The situation was undoubtably
unusual, in that both of the main parties were responsible for jerking a
once-regulated economy into the 'free market' regime, and hence associated
in voters' minds with the less palatable aspects of this process.
Nevertheless, the message is clear: voters will stomach only so much
upheaval, before demanding results.
Mr Bolger, National's leader, plainly knew this. At one point during the
campaign he was asked what conclusions should be drawn from Kim Campbell's
swingeing defeat in the Canadian elections. 'If you don't deliver jobs and
growth, you're down the gurgler,' he replied. His party has delivered a
little of both - although the unemployment rate has only just moved into
single-digit figures, and the more commendable growth figures have centred
on the export sector, with domestic benefits being slow to follow through.
As a result, he is still hanging on to power. But only just.
</TEXT>
