<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / International Capital Markets: Fear overcomes greed in the
US - The prospects for government bonds after last week's turmoil
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS and TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FEAR, at last, overcame greed in the US bond market last week. After a
fortnight of uncertainty about how much longer the bull run could last, the
bears emerged triumphant, triggering the biggest sell-off the bond market
had seen since prices began their climb a year ago.
By the end of the week the fall in prices had driven up the yield on the
benchmark 30-year government bond to 6.2 per cent, a level last seen in
August during its long journey downwards.
The blood-letting also spilled over into the equity markets, where worries
over the prospect of rising interest rates prompted a bout of heavy selling.
Warning signs of the bond market sell-off had been building up as government
figures increasingly pointed towards a strengthening of economic activity.
Investors typically regard such data as a threat of rising inflation, which
erodes the value of fixed-interest securities.
Already unnerved, the market last week gave up its resistance when
confronted by yet another barrage of figures pointing towards economic
growth.
The October index of manufacturing activity turned out to be higher than
expected; construction spending was up; new home sales showed the biggest
monthly increase in seven years; and strong October car sales confirmed that
consumers were in a spending mood.
The week ended with publication of data showing that payrolls expanded by
177,000 jobs last month - considerably more than the 150,000 or so that had
been expected - and that manufacturing employment had ended a seven-month
slide.
The result of all this good news was that, by Friday's close, the long bond
had shed nearly 3 1/2 points to 100 1/2 over the week - and investors were
looking anxiously ahead to key announcements to be made this week on the
October figures for inflation and retail sales.
Few are predicting any reversal in the bearish trend, at least in the short
term.
The spate of buoyant economic indicators has come as a sharp reminder that
inflation may not stay low for ever. Also, with the year-end looming,
portfolio managers are grappling with the inevitable temptation to realise
their gains by selling.
Meanwhile, the short end of the yield curve is being influenced by a heavy
supply of government debt: Smith Barney Shearson, the Wall Street brokerage
firm, estimates that Treasury issues of securities with maturities of three
years or less will gross nearly Dollars 175bn in November, raising Dollars
39bn in new cash.
In addition, the market is concerned that the Federal Reserve Board, mindful
of the economic pressures, will make its next interest rate move upwards
rather than downwards. Even so, nothing is forever - and in this case,
analysts do not believe the bond market bears will predominate for long.
Mr Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities' New York office,
points out there is a distinct feeling of deja vu about all the good
economic news.
The US saw much the same pattern last year - a weak first half followed by a
strong second half - only for things to start slowing down again as the new
year began.
Mr Brusca thinks that bond yields will keep on edging upwards to reach 6.5
per cent by the end of the year. But he is not alone in the belief that the
bulls will be back. After all, there are still plenty of negative factors
threatening to restrain economic growth.
The decline in defence spending is not going to go away; the effects of the
Clinton administration's tax increases will begin to bite next year; and the
cost to employers of the planned reforms in the health care system could
suppress employment growth.
Many analysts believe it will not be long before yields are back below the 6
per cent mark.
The economic fundamentals have not fundamentally altered. 'The big picture
for inflation is still very favourable,' says Mr Brusca, 'but there are
going to be some bumps along the road.' Last week, it seems, was just one of
them.
</TEXT>
