<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / International Company News: Franco-German talks lift telecom
stakes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TALKS between France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom about merging their
international business and then possibly linking with American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph are surprising only because of the size of the participants and
the potential scope of collaboration.
They are the world's three largest international telecommunications carriers
and an alliance could involve co-operation on ordinary international voice
traffic, data communications, video services and private networks.
The idea of telecoms operators trying to form global alliances or mergers is
not new. The industry has been a frenzy of matchmaking, as companies which
mostly grew up as protected national monopolies have sought to prepare for
the competitive global market.
Much of the focus has been on 'outsourcing' - the provision of global
services to multinational corporations. This year AT&amp;T established
Worldsource, an alliance linking it to Japan's KDD and Singapore Telecom.
The Swedish, Dutch and Swiss telecommunications carriers have created a
partnership called Unisource. France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom have
established Eunetcom.
But June's Dollars 5.3bn deal between British Telecommunications and MCI,
the second largest US carrier, involved not only a joint push into global
outsourcing but also BT's acquisition of 20 per cent of MCI, so preparing
the way for much deeper co-operation.
The Franco-German talks and discussions with AT&amp;T have been spurred by a
perceived need for a rival to BT/MCI. But before any alliance can be
consummated, it faces several hurdles.
On the commercial front, the partners will have to decide how much of their
business they wish to merge. They will also need to decide whether to
reinforce co-operation with equity stakes in one another and, if so, how
large.
France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom appear to want to merge all core
activities apart from domestic voice services, though even these might be
joined later. They also seem intent on bringing AT&amp;T in as a partner for
Eunetcom and perhaps co-operating with the US carrier on transatlantic
routes. But this could create strains with AT&amp;T, which appears to wish to be
a more equal partner and which could threaten to go it alone if not
satisfied.
On the regulatory front, much will depend on the details of any proposal.
The European Commission's competition authorities are likely to be concerned
at the potentially anti-competitive effect of a wide-ranging link between
France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom. It could compromise plans by the
competition directorate to require governments to open their telephone
markets to competition by 1998. A three-way link, bringing in AT&amp;T, could be
of even greater concern.
But other parts of the Commission might be more sympathetic. The French and
German operators would argue that by joining forces they would be in a good
position to create a pan-European 'intelligent network' - which would chime
in with the support in the Maastricht Treaty for pan-European networks.
</TEXT>
