<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / International Company News: Italy's 30-year domestic bond
move well received
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S first 30-year domestic government bond has been warmly greeted by
investors, in spite of political tensions which have depressed the lira and
bond prices.
The new bond, due later this month, takes Italy into the select group of
western industrialised states which have issued such long maturities. Until
the 1990s, most domestic bonds issued by the Rome government were either
short-term fixed-income treasury bills lasting up to a year or longer-term
floating-rate paper.
Although bankers had speculated last week that the Treasury was about to
break new ground, the 30-year bond was by no means certain in view of the
sudden upsurge in political tension over the future of President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro and the government of Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi. Treasury
officials suggested the decision to issue remained finely poised until
virtually the last minute.
But the treasury was encouraged to take the plunge by investors' appetite
for relatively high coupon debt. Interest rates on bonds have fallen sharply
in the past 12 months, with that on 10-year fixed rate government
securities, hitherto the longest, falling by virtually half to about 7 per
cent.
The new bond remains something of an experiment. The initial issue size is a
relatively cautious L2,000bn, with a gross coupon of 9 per cent. If
successful, it is likely to be followed by further tranches to create the
sort of liquidity essential to international investors.
Italy has already dabbled with 30-year maturities. In September, it launched
a Dollars 5.5bn global dollar bond, the world's biggest, which had a 30-year
component.
The global bond was the most conspicuous example of the treasury's much more
ambitious borrowing policy and reflects recent successes in tackling the
chronic budget deficit and inflation.
</TEXT>
