<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / International Company News: UBS cautious on outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNION Bank of Switzerland, the country's largest bank, will find it very
difficult to raise operating income next year, according to Mr Robert
Studer, chief executive.
In an interview, he said he was not pessimistic about the outlook for 1994,
but he did not expect trading activity to be as buoyant as it has been this
year.
In the first half of 1993, UBS's net income jumped by 89 per cent to
SFr1.29bn (Dollars 865m), achieving a 13 per cent return on equity, well
above its medium-term target of 10 per cent, and Mr Studer said that the
second half has remained very strong.
The main contributor to the bank's profit growth this year has been trading
income, which soared by 144 per cent to SFr1.55bn in the first half, thanks
to very active bond and stock markets and frequent turmoil in the foreign
exchange markets.
