<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / QMH accounts show hidden deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SERIES of deals under which Queens Moat Houses sold some of its German
hotels to directors and senior management and leased them back are detailed
in the troubled hotel group's accounts. The deals pushed DM270m (Pounds
110m) debt off balance sheet and bolstered group profits.
This, and the fact that Pounds 33.1m had been paid in unlawful dividends,
are the main breaches of company law and Stock Exchange regulations which
the new management has reported to the authorities.
The accounts are heavily qualified by new auditors Coopers &amp; Lybrand, which
said that as well as the group depending on a Pounds 1.1bn refinancing, the
present directors 'consider they do not have a sufficient understanding of
the 1991 property valuation to enable them to provide a full explanation for
the decline'. Property values fell by Pounds 1.34bn between the 1991 and
1992 balance sheet dates.
Also yesterday Mr Andrew Coppel, the new chief executive, responded to
suggestions by Mr John Bairstow, former chairman, that a report prepared by
accountants Grant Thornton at the request of QMH's banks should be
published. Mr Coppel said the report was 'a severe indictment of previous
management'.
According to the new management the German transactions should have been
notified to shareholders under Stock Exchange rules since they involved
directors. They included a deal concluded prior to the end of March 1993,
when the group's shares were suspended, backdated to midnight on December 31
1992. This involved selling shares in a subsidiary with assets of DM4.6m for
DM1m to Mr Jurgen Mannes, finance director of the German business.
This and other deals done in December, including the sale of five hotels for
DM146m, of which DM34m has yet to be received, could have added more than
Pounds 20m to group profits under its old accounting policies.
As well as Mr Mannes, the purchasers included Mr Gerald Bell, joint managing
director, and Mr Peter Bertholdt, another director of the German business.
QMH is attempting to amend the transactions and warns that it is 'not able
to quantify losses which might arise'.
The accounts also show that Mr John Williams, former property director,
received Pounds 1.2m in 1992 and Pounds 1.03m in 1991 including bonuses,
relating to the performance of a business he sold to QMH, and salary. The
1991 figure had not been disclosed in that year's accounts as the bonus of
Pounds 895,000 had been capitalised.
Mr Bairstow received a bonus of Pounds 128,400 in 1991. This was
consolidated into his remuneration in 1992 which rose from Pounds 208,800 to
Pounds 335,500, giving him total emoluments of Pounds 435,948, up from
Pounds 415,969.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
