<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Spending by British groups on takeovers in EC surges to
Pounds 5bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH companies spent about Pounds 5bn acquiring continental European
groups in a surge of overseas investment in the first 10 months of this
year, according to government figures.
The figures from the UK's Central Statistical Office show that British
companies' spending on overseas acquisitions between January and October was
two-thirds higher than in the same period in 1992.
The statistics suggest that strengthening balance sheets, coupled with the
gradual emergence of the UK economy from recession, have encouraged the rise
in cross-border spending.
Continuing recession in most European Community countries may also have
helped UK companies acquire continental businesses on attractive terms.
Hostile takeovers remain rare, however, and most EC deals continue to be
struck on agreed terms.
While the number of acquisitions completed by UK companies in the rest of
the EC has fallen, the size of many individual deals has risen sharply.
In some cases the figures have been distorted by large individual
acquisitions - such as the Kingfisher takeover of Darty, the French
electrical retailer, and the purchase by PowerGen and a US partner of an
east German coal field. But UK companies have, nevertheless, added
significantly to corporate assets in France, Germany, Spain and Italy.
Last week, Siebe, the UK controls and engineering group, launched a Pounds
184m rights issue to acquire Eckardt, a German process automation and
controls systems specialist. In recent months, UK companies such as
Courtaulds, Rugby Group, Northern Foods, Midlands Electricity and Amstrad
have all acquired businesses elsewhere in the EC.
Some of the upsurge in spending has been offset by the disposal by companies
of earlier acquisitions. UK disposals, within the EC so far this year were
worth about Pounds 571.5m, about half the level of 1992.
Interest in North American companies has also been reviving, despite the
dollar's recent strength. The CSO calculates that UK companies so far this
year have undertaken merger and acquisition deals in the US and Canada
valued at more than Pounds 5bn, twice the level in the whole of 1992. Even
so, the value of transatlantic deals is only about half the level in the
mid-1980s.
Separate CSO figures suggest the UK has itself continued to attract high
volumes of inward investment. So far this year, other EC nations have
invested Pounds 1.4bn into the UK, suggesting a final annual figure in line
with 1992. The CSO puts the figure from around the world so far this year at
more than Pounds 5bn, up by more than a quarter on 1992.
</TEXT>
