<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / The Lex Column: UK property
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Having slid down the snakes during the recession, fund managers are now
desperately trying to shin back up the ladders as recovery takes hold of the
property market. Some estimates suggest up to Pounds 10bn of investment
money is now looking for a home in bricks and mortar. Not surprisingly,
yields on prime property have fallen sharply as a result. Demand has been
particularly strong for central London offices where initial yields have
dropped to 7 per cent. That represents only a small premium over the yield
on long-dated gilts, suggesting that some fund managers' spectacles are
steaming up about the outlook. Indeed, after taking account of the fact that
many tenants are currently paying well above market rents, the implied yield
may be as low as 5 per cent.
Property yields may nudge still lower, especially if interest rates continue
to fall. After all, returns available elsewhere may be particularly meagre
in the brave new world of low inflation. But the trouble with investment by
default is that it invariably results in faulty investment. The danger is
that funds will repeat the errors of the 1980s, either paying too much for
prime properties, with little prospect of income or capital growth, or
settling for secondary locations, which may perform poorly over the long run
once development activity begins again. If Friday's fall in the equity
market were to continue, some of the pent-up demand could be released. At
some point, asset allocation committees might be tempted to switch funds
earmarked for property back into 'cheap' equities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
