<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / The Lex Column: Renault/Volvo
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Despite the breezy confidence of Volvo's chairman, there is a real risk that
the company's proposed merger with Renault may be blocked by dissident
shareholders. A failure to consummate the deal would come as a severe blow
to both companies. Renault would be mortified and devoid of obvious options.
Volvo's managers could perhaps stitch together an alternative alliance - a
partnership with Mitsubishi springs most obviously to mind. But, for both,
it would represent a huge loss of face and would delay essential
rationalisation.
The weight of necessity must make it probable that the merger will still be
effected, even if the terms have to be modified to appease the discontented.
An asset swap leaving Volvo with both truck businesses and Renault with all
the car operations represents one wild card option. But the industrial logic
of a full merger remains compelling: the geographical spread and product
ranges are highly complementary. Though Volvo's shareholders may quibble
about the valuation, the real issue boils down to whether they can trust the
French government. Mr Gyllenhammar, member of the Legion d'Honneur, clearly
has fewer doubts than many of his compatriots. But the recent ructions at
Air France add weight to shareholders' concerns.
At the very least, the French government will have to set a timetable for
privatising the merged company. That may be enough to win over Volvo's big
institutional shareholders, who could see an exit route. But the French
government's retention of a golden share seems to be non-negotiable.
</TEXT>
