<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Observer: Bags not me
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, 59-year-old Rudi Mueller, who stays on as chairman of UBS in
London, tells Observer that he has counted himself out as a candidate for
the chairmanship of the Stock Exchange when Sir Andrew Hugh Smith steps down
in just under a year. Planning to move back to Switzerland when he turns 62,
he considers two years to be far too short a time to devote to 'such an
important assignment'.
It would seem that the exchange has yet to identify Sir Andrew's successor,
which may be one reason why the headhunters had such difficulty in
recruiting a chief executive. Who would want to take on this already
daunting task whilst in the dark as to the identity of the next chairman?
After searching long and hard, and apparently even trying to persuade City
firms to second a senior figure for a couple of years, the exchange seems
finally to have struck lucky, and a chief executive, from outside the
current staff, is expected to be named at Thursday's council meeting. So now
what is called for is an imaginative choice of chairman.
Among those already on the board, one obvious candidate would be deputy
chairman Herschel Post, an American so anglicised that a fellow board member
had no idea Post was not English. Sir Michael Richardson has also been
mentioned, but the chairman of Smith New Court would have trouble
establishing his independence from the interests of the market-making
fraternity. Outside its own ranks, the board might consider Hoare Govett
chairman Peter Meinertzhagen. But why not cast the net far wider, outside
the membership of the exchange for once?
Out there, perhaps, is a fresh mind which would actually relish the
challenge.
</TEXT>
