<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Leading Article: Mr Yeltsin and democracy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE carte blanche which western leaders have given to President Boris
Yeltsin is increasingly under challenge from Russian parliamentarians and
press. This is right. Russia wishes to be accepted both as a democratic
state and as an economy at least approaching the market, so it must expect
to be judged by the prevailing norms of both as it prepares for
parliamentary elections.
They take place in the shadow of a parliament still bearing the scorch marks
of its suppression by the army last month. The end of the parliament means
that the constitution, which crucially deals with the division of powers
between the presidency and the legislature, is being framed without any
representation whatever from the latter.
The assault on parliament has been, as Mr Yeltsin slyly noted last week, a
lesson hastily taken by every locus of power in the country; all treat him
now with greater deference. Like the much bloodier and much less justifiable
suppression of dissent in Tiananmen Square, it has had the effect of
strengthening the centre and of encouraging foreign investment (in Russia's
case, this is still tentative); but it has also unmistakably inhibited
debate, and given the president nearly all the aces.
Compromises
Thus, in the construction of the new constitution, the compromises which Mr
Yeltsin's team had made in earlier drafts to the parliament, to the regions
and to political forces have largely been cancelled. When the constitution
is unveiled on Wednesday, it seems that parliament's first term will be
limited to two years and that, in the second term, the deputies of the upper
house who are to be elected in this December's polls will thereafter be
nominated by the regions and the republics. This is likely to result in the
senior chamber being dominated by regional placemen answerable to
presidentially-appointed governors rather than to the people.
Meanwhile, the conduct of the election has been uneven. The parties of the
far left and right have suffered significant problems in securing office
space and telephones, while those who have fielded candidates who were
deputies in the old parliament have seen their phones cut off and the
tenancy of their flats threatened.
The media has been unbalanced in favour of the pro-presidential parties.
Newspapers, especially the increasingly influential regional ones, are
largely for the Yeltsin parties; they are also supported by the state
budget. Some anti-Yeltsin voices, like the popular, far-right television
programme 600 Seconds, remain banned.
Trauma
Now, it appears, Mr Yeltsin has decided not to hold pre-term presidential
elections next June, as he had earlier insisted he would. What could have
been an opportunity for renewing his mandate after the trauma of the last
few months is to be forgone in favour of a continuation of his presidency
until its appointed end in June 1996.
All of this gives occasion for some alarm. The field is not level, the media
are not balanced, the rules are being made up on the hoof. The only source
of ultimate authority is the president.
But this does not yet amount to authoritarian rule. It is rather the product
of confusion, conflicting ambitions and lack of democratic experience. What
still shines through the twists and turns of the Yeltsin camp is the intense
desire to create the institutions of a functioning democratic state and of a
functioning market economy. The vacuum where a balance of powers should be
is due to the suicidal course taken by parliament in attempting to pit
itself uncompromisingly against the executive power, ultimately up to the
use of arms. Those who are left holding the instruments of the state can do
no other than construct a system in this vacuum.
Mr Yeltsin's decision to soldier on to 1996 is not alarming in itself; a
greater worry is that his health and energy will not stand it, and that the
parliament he is bringing to life will find itself too constrained in its
role to develop as a responsible legislature. But overall, the vigour of the
pre-election process and the diversity of view shown a mere five weeks after
the fate of the state itself was briefly in the balance, is impressive and
reassuring. Mr Yeltsin remains the best bet yet.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
