<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Leading Article: Forward to Tory basics
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AS BRITISH cabinet ministers prepare for a new session of parliament, they
have before them a document from their party leader which urges the virtues
of common sense and 'basic' Conservative values. It is described variously
as an aide-memoire and an interim manifesto.
Mr John Major's tract is in some respects an understandable reaction to the
difficulties of governing with a small majority at a time of continuing
economic uncertainty. Last week's fevered trimming on rail privatisation,
along with revisionism on issues such as police reform, has again put the
government in an unflattering light.
The prime minister, however, will make a serious mistake if he tries to set
his party's compass with reference to the past. Only some of his current
difficulties derive from his slender parliamentary majority; others are
caused by a lack of belief among ministers over what they are trying to
achieve. Nowhere is this more evident than in policies to privatise services
and cut the size of the public sector, a field which gave the Thatcher
administration of the 1980s much of its cutting edge.
Slimming the public sector has not been abandoned as a policy objective but
it is being pursued without strategy or vigour. Mr John MacGregor, the
transport secretary, has doggedly pressed ahead with rail privatisation but
done little to articulate the benefits that will flow from it. The result is
that the public fears that privatisation will lead to fare increases and
service cuts.
Similarly, Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister, has failed
to inject dynamism into his programme of contracting out civil service work.
Last week he revealed a big shortfall in targeted savings. Contractors have
accused the civil service of dragging its feet. There have also been cases
of the government recoiling from controversial privatisations, notably that
of the Post Office.
Defensive
It is important that this defensive approach is not carried through into the
next session of parliament. Decisions will soon be needed on whether to
privatise nuclear power, London's buses and the Forestry Commission. There
is also unfinished work on gas privatisation. Mr Michael Heseltine, trade
and industry secretary, must decide whether to break up British Gas.
Similarly, work remains to be done on the government's initiative of
attracting private capital for public infrastructure projects. Currently, it
is moving at a snail's pace. A more radical approach to the civil service is
also needed. As well as market-testing Whitehall functions, full
privatisation should be more widely explored.
Determination
If ministers are to get their privatisation initiative back on track, they
will need to display four qualities that have been conspicuously lacking in
past months. First, determination will be needed to override the forces in
favour of maintaining the status quo. There will always be interest groups
with well-honed arguments for why things cannot be changed. While these
cannot be dismissed, ministers must cut through the special pleading and
isolate any genuine public interests that need to be protected.
Second, imagination will be needed in refining the details of policy where
genuine public interests are at stake. The gas industry is a good example.
Ways must be found to combine the benefits of competition while ensuring
that the subsequent erosion of cross-subsidies does not lead to higher bills
for the poorest customers.
Third, pragmatism is required if entrepreneurs are to invest in privatised
rail services, contracting-out opportunities or public infrastructure
projects. Government inflexibility in defining opportunities has been
highlighted as a principal reason why private-sector interest is waning.
Finally, better presentation will be needed to convince a doubting public of
the virtues, in terms of efficiency and choice, of more competition and a
reduced role for the state. It will not be good enough to state blind faith
in the power of competitive markets. Ministers will need to articulate
practical benefits.
All this requires a lead from the top. The perils of governing with a small
majority are bad enough. Mr Major should remember that the perils of
governing without direction are even worse.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
