<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Time to combat the rot: The initiatives of Stanley Kalms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Stanley Kalms, chairman of the Dixons electrical goods retailer, is tired
of headlines about crime and the disintegration of UK urban life, and has
decided to do something about it.
He is planning to sponsor a school in Yorkshire with Pounds 100,000 of his
own money, and is thinking about setting up a private police force with
other British store chains. These moves underline Mr Kalm's belief that
business people should take on wider responsibilities to combat what he
describes as the 'nasty infection' taking root in Britain's social fabric.
Mr Kalms, a supporter of the Conservative party, is an unusual
industrialist. While acknowledging the economic growth brought about by the
unleashing of market forces in the 1980s, he stresses their role in helping
to create conditions for high unemployment, a growing crime wave and a
criminal justice system that he reckons has 'fallen asleep'.
At times sounding like Mr Tony Blair, the Labour home affairs spokesman, Mr
Kalms accuses the government of being slow to work out the link between
inadequacies in the education system and poorly trained young people who
turn to crime. He reckons industry has a vital job in helping schools
produce adaptable youngsters who will find productive employment.
The 61-year-old Mr Kalms points out that, ironically, many of the maxims of
Baroness Thatcher's 'enterprise culture' are being applied to breaking the
law. 'The crime industry is a major profession, turning out new products at
a rate of knots,' he says.
His interests in social regeneration have developed during a 45-year
business career spent entirely with Dixons - which he has built up from one
shop owned by his father to a 1,000-store business with annual sales of
nearly Pounds 2bn. Among his attributes are a gift for plain speaking and
good political connections: he is a member of the group of business
executives occasionally invited to Downing Street for informal discussions
with Mr John Major.
His non-business interests are illustrated by his scheme to sponsor a school
to help it specialise in science and computers. Dixons is already sponsoring
a school in Bradford, Yorkshire, as part of the government's city technology
college programme, designed to teach more youngsters about industry.
Mr Kalms says there is a direct connection between education - or lack of it
 -and crime. While he is keen to improve training for young people, he says
industrialists should not sit on their hands while their businesses suffer
through what he decribes as a breakdown of law and order. That explains why
he is talking to other big retailers about setting up joint security squads
to patrol high streets to protect property and shoppers from criminals. But
he stresses this does not mean behaving irresponsibly. Mr Kalms has seconded
one of his Dixons executives to the Home Office for six months to ensure any
new action by the private sector on security squads is co-ordinated with the
police.
Mr Kalms welcomes the results of government action in the 1980s to privatise
nationalised industries and reduce trade union power. But he links the
free-market approach - involving greater competition and fewer restrictions
on sacking people - to high unemployment. He reckons business has a role to
play in tackling social problems, partly because 'industry rode the tiger
and prospered' in the 1980s.
He also reckons companies are in a good position to impart skills to young
people by helping 'create a seamless system of education through to
employment'. He is enthusisatic, for example, about how Dixons' college in
Bradford asked its pupils to design a new plastic bag for the company's
shops. 'The people who worked on this have got a total understanding of
commercial culture. After they leave school they'll be snapped up.'
With public policy looming large in Mr Kalms's arguments, what advice does
he have for the chancellor ahead of the Budget due later this month? The
Dixons chairman acknowledges Mr Kenneth Clarke's need to bring down the
Pounds 50bn borrowing requirement. But sounding emphatically unThatcherite,
he suggests the government should consider tax rises to curb the deficit, on
the grounds that public spending cuts could make social problems worse.
'The government's greatest priority should be safeguarding the community,'
he says.
</TEXT>
