<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 93 / Japan's battle for the back room: The new government is
wrestling the bureaucrats for control of the ministries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The shirt-sleeved samurai of Tokyo's public administration are sharpening
their swords for a behind-the-scenes power struggle that is changing the way
Japan is governed.
Having spent most of the postwar years building up Japan's economic might
across the world, they are now engaged in a different battle, right in their
own corridors.
This time, the challenge comes from the new Japanese government, whose plans
to cut regulations and reform the political system have jolted the
traditionally cosy relationship between politicians and bureaucrats.
The upheaval triggered by the end of nearly four decades of rule by the
Liberal Democratic party, plus economic recession, has exposed weaknesses in
the old consensus, once seen as a strength.
An indication of just who is on top will come today with the publication of
an interim report from a government panel set up by Prime Minister Morihiro
Hosokawa. The panel - under Mr Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of the Keidanren
business federation - was asked to advise on how the existing deregulation
plans - which spell anathema to several departments and ministries - could
be beefed up.
So far, the early rounds of the struggle have left the strongest departments
on top. But in the long term, the bureaucrats look as if they will have to
get used to sharing more power with the politicians.
The bureaucrats' public image is poor, tainted by international trade rows,
foreign policy mishaps and construction industry scandals. The newly
appointed Socialist construction minister is trying, for the first time, to
hold officials publicly responsible for failing to prevent bribery.
The government's image, by contrast, has never been better, as testified by
Mr Hosokawa's record popularity ratings of just over 73 per cent. However,
Mr Hosokawa will need more than style to make up for the fact that he does
not have the LDP's formidable back-room power structure, which collapsed
after its July election defeat.
Mr Hosokawa's unstable seven-party coalition replaced a network of LDP
policy committees, which used to restrain individual ministries by
arbitrating between them and keeping tabs on new legislation from the
earliest drafts. Under the LDP system, politically appointed ministers were
frequently rotated, giving them little time to master their dossiers and
hence little chance to make trouble.
Many of the coalition government's ministers are even newer to their jobs
than their LDP predecessors, so creating a temporary vacuum that the public
administration is doing its best to fill before a more stable government
comes along.
To the worry of other government departments, the first victory in the
battle with the politicians went to the powerful finance ministry, which
succeeded in getting one of its former officials, Mr Hirohisa Fujii, chosen
as finance minister.
The finance ministry also succeeded in setting spending ceilings for all
other departments for next year's budget, a process formerly carried out
only after consultation with the LDP committees. The move is thought to have
limited the new government's freedom to draw up spending packages to
stimulate the flagging economy.
'The collapse of the dual structure that was composed of the LDP and
government organs . . . will inevitably strengthen the ministry's power. We
are worried about that,' says a senior official at the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry.
Senior finance ministry officials do not see it that way. 'Only we have the
expertise . . . It is necessary to compensate for the weakness of political
leadership,' one says.
The next victory - which might prove short-lived - went to the ministries
which administer the bulk of Japan's more than 10,000 official regulations:
transport, construction, post and telecommunications. The ministries
successfully resisted LDP attempts to cut red tape and are trying to
continue that way. However, there is one sign that new ministers are getting
their way. The new transport and construction ministers meet often to try to
co-ordinate policy in areas like urban development and infrastructure
spending, where their departments were sometimes at loggerheads.
This co-operation is the exception at the moment. When Mr Hosokawa asked
ministries to come up with a package of deregulation measures in September,
they produced a mere 94 ideas. They are now striving to curb the
government's efforts to push deregulation further. Mr Hosokawa rejected as
too vague the government panel's draft proposals and sent it back to the
drawing board.
Early bureaucratic triumphs could prove merely tactical. One consequence of
reform - which is likely to be agreed by this government - will be to
encourage a breed of more competent politicians.
First, they will be elected more on policies than on their ability to
channel business opportunities and cash to supporters. And those policies
might not correspond with the public administration's ideas.
Second, bureaucratic influence in parliament will be curbed. Mr Hosokawa has
reduced the number of senior officials allowed to reply to parliamentary
questions on ministers' behalf, and aims eventually to throw them out of the
chamber.
The extent to which Japanese parliamentarians used to behave as if
government were in the hands of the public administration is illustrated by
a former director-general of the LDP defence agency (Japan's equivalent of a
defence ministry). He once referred a question to an official on the grounds
that 'the matter is important'. That should become a joke of the past.
The progress being made by the Hosokawa government in wearing down finance
ministry opposition to a cut in income taxes is another example of the
fragility of bureaucrats' initial victories.
Another area where the political class is on the offensive is over plans,
now in the early stages, to reduce the number of government ministries and
agencies from 21 to just six. That idea was put forward last week by a panel
on administrative reform, whose report is otherwise short on detail, an
indication of the extent to which bureaucrats have managed to water it down.
Nevertheless, the surviving recommendations were received with delight by Mr
Hosokawa, who promises to carry them out in full.
Japan's bureaucracy was already approaching a watershed before the emergence
of these latest pressures to surrender some of its power.
A prime example is Miti, admired worldwide as the planner of Japan's
industrial strength. Now that the car and electronics industries are near
maturity, Miti is looking for a new role and a new growth industry, so far
without success. Some believe the ministry has partly lost its touch by
being late to appreciate the importance of microcomputers.
'Miti's basic role was to encourage Japanese industry by deploying industry
policy. But now there is an export surplus and the market is saturated at
home, so there is very little for Miti to do,' says Mr Naohiro Amaya, a
former Miti vice-minister, the top bureaucratic job there.
The agriculture department is also looking for a fresh role. Its traditional
job of defending the rice industry and ensuring Japan's food
self-sufficiency is being fast eroded. The ministry appears paralysed by the
growing pressure on Japan to phase out its ban on rice imports, as a
condition of concluding the Uruguay Round of world trade talks.
However, it would be wrong to undervalue the Japanese bureaucracy's skills.
A career serving national interests in the public administration is still
seen as the ideal for the majority of Japan's brightest and best young
people.
The heart of the problem is that the interest the bureaucrats are supposed
to serve, beyond defending their own ministries' power, is becoming less
clear.
'Until recently, their goal was clear cut, to catch up with and surpass
western economies. Now that the bureaucracy has carried out this target . .
. it is time for Japan to set new goals,' Mr Amaya says. 'This is not as
easy as making good cars. Nobody can tell you how to do it. There is no
blueprint.'
It is uncertain whether the outcome of the present power struggle will make
Japan any better at setting new goals for itself. Mr Hosokawa's government
clearly hopes that it will. As Mr Amaya says: 'It is the first move in a
long game of trial and error.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P9199 General Government, NEC.
    P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
